{"title_page": "Dawn Fraser", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian swimmer and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Dawn Fraser\n| image          = Dawn Fraser.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Fraser in May 2012\n| fullname       = Dawn Fraser\n| nicknames      = \"Dawny\" \n| national_team  = {{AUS}}\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle & Butterfly]]\n| club           =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1937|9|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Balmain, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{convert|1.72|m|ftin}}\n| weight         = {{convert|67|kg|lb}}\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | Australia}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Melbourne]] | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 1956 Melbourne | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome]] | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1964 Summer Olympics|1964 Tokyo]] | [[Swimming at the 1964 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1956 Melbourne | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1960 Rome | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1960 Rome | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1964 Tokyo | [[Swimming at the 1964 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1958 Cardiff]] | 110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1958 Cardiff | 4\u00d7110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1962 Perth]] | 110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 440 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 4\u00d7110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 4\u00d7110 yd medley}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1958 Cardiff | 440 yd freestyle}}\n}}\n'''Dawn Fraser''', {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AC|MBE}} (born 4 September 1937) is an Australian freestyle champion [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and former politician.  She is one of only three swimmers to have won the same Olympic individual event three times \u2013 in her case the women's 100-metre freestyle.<ref name=r1>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fr/dawn-fraser-1.html Dawn Fraser] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917220142/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fr/dawn-fraser-1.html |date=17 September 2013 }}. sports-reference.com</ref>\n\nWithin Australia, she is often known for her controversial behaviour and [[larrikinism|larrikin]] character as much as for her athletic ability.\n\n==Early life==\nFraser was born in the Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales]] in 1937 into a poor working-class family, the youngest of eight children.<ref name=\"icons\">{{cite book |title=Icons of Women's Sport |last1=Boyer Sagert |first1=Kelley |last2=Overman |first2=Steven J. |pages=137\u2013152 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-313-38549-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_kTU8LfcqAC&lpg=PA138&ots=PSRWjXU4sq&dq=%22Dawn%20Fraser%22%20father%20%20Balmain%201937&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q=%22Dawn%20Fraser%22&f=false |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> Her father, Kenneth Fraser, was from [[Embo]], Scotland.<ref name=\"northern_times\">{{cite web |url=http://www.northern-times.co.uk/News/Olympic-swim-star-makes-surprise-visit-30082012.htm |title=Olympic swim star makes surprise visit |last=McMorran |first=Caroline |publisher=The Northern Times |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> She was spotted at the early age of 14 by Sydney coach Harry Gallagher swimming at the local sea baths.\n\n==Swimming career==\nFraser won eight Olympic medals, including four gold medals, and six [[Commonwealth Games]] gold medals. She also held 39 records. The 100 metres freestyle record was hers for 15 years from 1 December 1956 to 8 January 1972.\n\nShe is the first of only three swimmers in Olympic history ([[Krisztina Egerszegi]] of Hungary and [[Michael Phelps]] of the United States being the two others) to have won individual gold medals for the same event at three successive Olympics [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (women)|(100 metres freestyle \u2013 1956, 1960, 1964)]].\n\nIn October 1962, she became the first woman to swim 100 metres freestyle in less than one minute.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Clarkson|title=Champion's world time in 110 yds|newspaper=The Sun-Herald|page=67|date=28 October 1962}}</ref> It was not until 1972, eight years after Fraser retired, that her 100m hello darkness my onld friend\nrecord of 58.9 secs was broken.<ref>{{cite news|title=Swim contest a spectacular of records|publisher=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]], [[Reuters]]|work=The Sun-Herald|page=107|date=2 May 1971}}</ref> \n\nSeveral weeks before the 1964 Olympics, Fraser was injured in a car crash that resulted in the death of her mother Rose. Her sister and a friend were also travelling in Fraser's car when it crashed, but they survived.<ref>{{cite web|title=I killed my mother|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/08/09/1091903458221.html|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref> This was a fresh tragedy for Fraser and her family following her older brother's death from leukemia in 1950, and her father died after a long battle against cancer in 1960.\n\n==Controversy==\nDuring the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, Fraser angered swimming team sponsors and the Australian Swimming Union (ASU) by marching in the opening ceremony against their wishes, and wearing an older swimming costume in competition, as she found it more comfortable than the one supplied by the sponsors. She was accused of stealing an Olympic flag from a flagpole outside [[Hirohito|Emperor Hirohito]]'s palace, the [[K\u014dkyo]]. She was arrested but released without charge. In the end she was given the flag as a souvenir.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dawn Fraser: still kicking:|url = http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|website = Sunday Profile, ABC|accessdate = 4 November 2015|date = 15 April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212085422/http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|archivedate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> However, the Australian Swimming Union suspended her for 10 years. They relented a few months before the 1968 Games but by then it was too late for Fraser, at 31, to prepare. She later denied having swum the moat to steal the flag, telling ''The Times'' in 1991: \"There's no way I would have swum that moat. I was terrified of dirty water and that moat was filthy. There's no way I'd have dipped my toe in it.\"{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Post-swimming activities==\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Dawn Fraser\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AC|MBE}}\n|constituency_MP  = [[Electoral district of Balmain|Balmain]]\n|parliament       = New South Wales\n|term_start       = 19 March 1988\n|term_end         = 25 May 1991\n|predecessor      = [[Peter Crawford (Australian politician)|Peter Crawford]]\n|successor        = District abolished\n}}\nFraser became a publican at the [[Balmain, New South Wales#Drinking establishments|Riverview Hotel]], Balmain, and took up swimming coaching. In 1988, she was elected as an [[independent politician|independent]] to the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Electoral district of Balmain|seat of Balmain]]. That electorate was abolished in 1991, and after she failed to win the new seat of [[Electoral district of Port Jackson|Port Jackson]], she retired from politics.<ref name=r1/><ref name=\"Dawn Fraser NSW Parl\">{{Cite NSW Parliament |id=1947 |former=Yes |access-date=13 May 2019 |title=Ms Dawn Fraser (1937\u2013 ) }}</ref>\nFraser is a high-profile supporter and a board director of the [[Wests Tigers]] [[NRL]] club.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/benji-marshall-good-natured-dawn-fraser/story-fn3dxity-1226121182177</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nShe was named the [[Australian of the Year]] in 1964,<ref>{{cite book | author=Lewis, Wendy | title=Australians of the Year | publisher=Pier 9 Press | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-74196-809-5 | authorlink=Wendy Lewis }}</ref> was inducted into the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] in 1965,<ref name=ishofprofile>International Swimming Hall of Fame, Honorees, [http://www.ishof.org/dawn-fraser-(aus).html  Dawn Fraser (AUS)].  Retrieved 17 March 2015.</ref> was made a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1967,<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1088356&search_type=advanced&showInd=true It's an Honour] \u2013 Member of the Order of the British Empire</ref> and appointed an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO) in 1998.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=872625&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] \u2013 Officer of the Order of Australia</ref>  Also in 1998, she was voted Australia's greatest female athlete in history.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}  She was named Australian Female Athlete of the Century by the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]],<ref name=\"smh2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/fraser-named-greatest-despite-push-for-skater-20130227-2f6dm.html|title=Fraser named greatest despite push for skater|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=28 February 2013|first=Chris|last=Wilson|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> who had inducted her as their first female member in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=79&memberType=legends|title=Dawn Fraser AO MBE|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>  In 1999 the [[International Olympic Committee]] named her the World's Greatest Living Female Water Sports Champion.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} on 14 July 2000, Fraser was awarded the [[Australian Sports Medal]] for \"outstanding contribution as a swimming competitor\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Dawn Fraser|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=980531&search_type=simple&showInd=true|publisher=Australian Honours Database|accessdate=8 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of the bearers of the [[Olympic Torch]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]] of the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney. She carried the Olympic Torch at the stadium, as one of the bearers for the final segment, before the lighting of the [[Olympic Flame]].\n\nThe [[Australian Sport Awards]] includes an award named in honour of and presented by Fraser. The sea baths in Balmain where she swam were named the [[Dawn Fraser Swimming Pool]] in her honour in 1964,<ref>http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/visit/ViewAttractionDetail.aspx?ID=5001040#</ref> and in 1992, the [[State Transit Authority]] named a [[Sydney RiverCats|RiverCat ferry]] after Fraser.\n\nAs part of the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)|2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]] she was advanced to a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/2001256 |title=FRASER, Dawn |work=It's An Honour |publisher=Australian Government |date=11 June 2018 |accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In film==\nIn 1979, a movie called ''[[Dawn!]]'' was made about Fraser's life and career. It starred Bronwyn Mackay-Payne as Fraser.\n\nFraser was played by [[Melissa Thomas]] in the 2003 film ''[[Swimming Upstream]]''. Fraser herself is credited in the film as Dawn Fraser's coach.\nOn  1 September 2015, Dawn Fraser featured on Season 7, Episode 5 of the [[SBS (Australian TV channel)|SBS]] genealogy television series [[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]], which traced her heritage back to South America.\n\n== Personal life ==\nFraser married Gary Ware on 30 January 1965 at St Stephens Church, Macquarie Street, Sydney.<ref name=sl-pic-wedding>{{cite web |last1=Hickson|first1=Jack |title=Dawn Fraser's wedding to Gary Ware, St. Stephen's Church, Sydney |url=http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/item/itemDetailPaged.aspx?itemID=98512 |website=acms.sl.nsw.gov.au |date=30 January 1965 |publisher=State Library of NSW |accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The marriage was short-lived. She has one daughter from the marriage, Dawn-Lorraine, who has a son, Jackson. Dawn Fraser suffered from severe asthma.<ref name=abc-kicking>{{cite interview|author=Fraser, Dawn|interviewer=Attard, Monica|title=Dawn Fraser: still kicking|url=http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|website=Sunday Profile www.abc.net.a|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=21 December 2014|date=15 April  2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212085422/http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|archive-date=12 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=smh-smiling>{{cite news |last1=Hardy|first1=Karen |title=Dawn Fraser still smiling |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/dawn-fraser-still-smiling-20131213-2zarg.html |accessdate=21 December 2014 |work=The Sydney Morining Herald |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFraser has drawn negative criticism for public comments in 1997 when she said \"I'm sick and tired of the immigrants that are coming into my country\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/from-olympic-bans-to-one-nation-dawn-fraser-no-stranger-to-controversy-20150707-gi6sgw.html#ixzz3kkQ1HLXL|title=From Olympic bans to One Nation: Dawn Fraser no stranger to controversy|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> and in 2015 when she told Australian tennis players [[Nick Kyrgios]] and [[Bernard Tomic]] to \"go back to where their fathers or parents came from\u201d. \"I've always spoken the truth,\" Fraser said. \"It was the way I was brought up, to be honest and to tell the truth.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/> These views have been described as racist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/tennis/olympic-legend-dawn-fraser-launches-racist-attack-on-nick-kyrgios/story-fnu2pjj2-1227431907759|title=Dawn Fraser attacks Nick Kyrgios after Wimbledon 2015 loss|date=7 July 2015|work=NewsComAu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/dawn-frasers-comments-about-kyrgios-and-tomic-were-racist-say-experts-20150707-gi70b6.html |title=Dawn Fraser's comments about Kyrgios and Tomic were racist, say experts |first1=Angus |last1=Holland |date=July 7, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |access-date=August 13, 2016 }}</ref> She subsequently apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jul/07/dawn-fraser-sorry-for-racist-outburst-on-nick-kyrgios-and-bernard-tomic |title=Dawn Fraser sorry for 'racist' outburst on Nick Kyrgios and Bernard Tomic |date=July 7, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=August 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Olympic accomplishments==\n[[File:Dawn Fraser 1958.jpg|thumb|Dawn Fraser in 1958]]\n[[File:Dawn Fraser and Ilsa Konrads at the Australian National Swimming Championships and Olympic Trials, North Sydney Olympic Pool, 27 February 1960.jpeg|thumb|Dawn Fraser and Ilsa Konrads at the Australian National Swimming Championships and Olympic Trials, North Sydney Olympic Pool, 27 February 1960]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| '''Event'''\n| align=\"center\" | '''Time'''\n| align=\"center\" | '''Place'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1956 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 1:02.0\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"00CC33\" align=\"center\" | '''WR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 5:02.5\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:17.1\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"00CC33\" align=\"center\" | '''WR'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1960 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 1:01.2\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"orange\" align=\"center\" | '''OR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 4:58.5\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 5th\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:11.3\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Medley Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:45.9\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1964 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 59.5\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"orange\" align=\"center\" | '''OR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 4:47.6\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 4th\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:06.9\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Medley Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:52.3\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 9th\n|}\n\n*[[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1962 Perth Commonwealth Games]]\n**110&nbsp;yards freestyle \u2013 gold medal\n**440&nbsp;yards freestyle \u2013 gold medal\n**4 x 110&nbsp;yards (4 x 100.58 metres) freestyle relay \u2013 gold medal\n**4 x 110&nbsp;yards (4 x 100.58 metres) medley relay \u2013 gold medal\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of members of the International Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (women)]]\n* [[World record progression 100 metres freestyle]]\n* [[World record progression 200 metres freestyle]]\n* [[World record progression 4 \u00d7 100 metres freestyle relay]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.olympics.com.au/athletes.cfm?AthleteID=2209 Dawn Fraser] &ndash; Olympic athlete profile at Australian Olympic Committee\n* [http://www.dawnfraser.com.au/records.htm Dawn Fraser's world records]\n* [http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0386b.htm  Dawn Fraser] &ndash; article in ''The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia''\n* [http://www.ishof.org/dawn-fraser-(aus).html  Dawn Fraser (AUS)] &ndash; Honor Swimmer profile at International Swimming Hall of Fame\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Peter Crawford (Australian politician)|Peter Crawford]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = Member for [[Electoral district of Balmain|Balmain]] | years=1988&ndash;1991}}\n{{s-non | reason= District abolished }}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Willy den Ouden ]]|title=[[World record progression 100 metres freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle<br>world record holder (long course)]]|years=21 February 1956 \u2013 3 March 1956|after=[[Cocky Gastelaars]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Cocky Gastelaars]]|title=[[World record progression 100 metres freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle<br>world record holder (long course)]]|years=25 August 1956 \u2013 20 October 1956|after=[[Lorraine Crapp]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 100 m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 4x100 m Freestyle Relay Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 100m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 400m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 4x100m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Associated Press Female Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{Australians of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraser, Dawn}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Female freestyle swimmers]]\n[[Category:Australian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:World record setters in swimming]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the Parliament of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Australian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:Sport Australia Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Women members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian swimmer and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Dawn Fraser\n| image          = Dawn Fraser.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Fraser in May 2012\n| fullname       = Dawn Fraser\n| nicknames      = \"Dawny\" \n| national_team  = {{AUS}}\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle & Butterfly]]\n| club           =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1937|9|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Balmain, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{convert|1.72|m|ftin}}\n| weight         = {{convert|67|kg|lb}}\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | Australia}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Melbourne]] | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 1956 Melbourne | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome]] | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1964 Summer Olympics|1964 Tokyo]] | [[Swimming at the 1964 Summer Olympics - Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1956 Melbourne | [[Swimming at the 1956 Summer Olympics - Women's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1960 Rome | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1960 Rome | [[Swimming at the 1960 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1964 Tokyo | [[Swimming at the 1964 Summer Olympics - Women's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1958 Cardiff]] | 110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1958 Cardiff | 4\u00d7110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1962 Perth]] | 110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 440 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 4\u00d7110 yd freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 Perth | 4\u00d7110 yd medley}}\n{{MedalSilver | 1958 Cardiff | 440 yd freestyle}}\n}}\n'''Dawn Fraser''', {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AC|MBE}} (born 4 September 1937) is an Australian freestyle champion [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and former politician.  She is one of only three swimmers to have won the same Olympic individual event three times \u2013 in her case the women's 100-metre freestyle.<ref name=r1>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fr/dawn-fraser-1.html Dawn Fraser] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917220142/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fr/dawn-fraser-1.html |date=17 September 2013 }}. sports-reference.com</ref>\n\nWithin Australia, she is often known for her controversial behaviour and [[larrikinism|larrikin]] character as much as for her athletic ability.\n\n==Early life==\nFraser was born in the Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales]] in 1937 into a poor working-class family, the youngest of eight children.<ref name=\"icons\">{{cite book |title=Icons of Women's Sport |last1=Boyer Sagert |first1=Kelley |last2=Overman |first2=Steven J. |pages=137\u2013152 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-313-38549-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_kTU8LfcqAC&lpg=PA138&ots=PSRWjXU4sq&dq=%22Dawn%20Fraser%22%20father%20%20Balmain%201937&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q=%22Dawn%20Fraser%22&f=false |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> Her father, Kenneth Fraser, was from [[Embo]], Scotland.<ref name=\"northern_times\">{{cite web |url=http://www.northern-times.co.uk/News/Olympic-swim-star-makes-surprise-visit-30082012.htm |title=Olympic swim star makes surprise visit |last=McMorran |first=Caroline |publisher=The Northern Times |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> She was spotted at the early age of 14 by Sydney coach Harry Gallagher swimming at the local sea baths.\n\n==Swimming career==\nFraser won eight Olympic medals, including four gold medals, and six [[Commonwealth Games]] gold medals. She also held 39 records. The 100 metres freestyle record was hers for 15 years from 1 December 1956 to 8 January 1972.\n\nShe is the first of only three swimmers in Olympic history ([[Krisztina Egerszegi]] of Hungary and [[Michael Phelps]] of the United States being the two others) to have won individual gold medals for the same event at three successive Olympics [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (women)|(100 metres freestyle \u2013 1956, 1960, 1964)]].\n\nIn October 1962, she became the first woman to swim 100 metres freestyle in less than one minute.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Clarkson|title=Champion's world time in 110 yds|newspaper=The Sun-Herald|page=67|date=28 October 1962}}</ref> It was not until 1972, eight years after Fraser retired, that her 100m record of 58.9 secs was broken.<ref>{{cite news|title=Swim contest a spectacular of records|publisher=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]], [[Reuters]]|work=The Sun-Herald|page=107|date=2 May 1971}}</ref>\n\nSeveral weeks before the 1964 Olympics, Fraser was injured in a car crash that resulted in the death of her mother Rose. Her sister and a friend were also travelling in Fraser's car when it crashed, but they survived.<ref>{{cite web|title=I killed my mother|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/08/09/1091903458221.html|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref> This was a fresh tragedy for Fraser and her family following her older brother's death from leukemia in 1950, and her father died after a long battle against cancer in 1960.\n==Controversy==\nDuring the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, Fraser angered swimming team sponsors and the Australian Swimming Union (ASU) by marching in the opening ceremony against their wishes, and wearing an older swimming costume in competition, as she found it more comfortable than the one supplied by the sponsors. She was accused of stealing an Olympic flag from a flagpole outside [[Hirohito|Emperor Hirohito]]'s palace, the [[K\u014dkyo]]. She was arrested but released without charge. In the end she was given the flag as a souvenir.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dawn Fraser: still kicking:|url = http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|website = Sunday Profile, ABC|accessdate = 4 November 2015|date = 15 April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212085422/http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|archivedate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> However, the Australian Swimming Union suspended her for 10 years. They relented a few months before the 1968 Games but by then it was too late for Fraser, at 31, to prepare. She later denied having swum the moat to steal the flag, telling ''The Times'' in 1991: \"There's no way I would have swum that moat. I was terrified of dirty water and that moat was filthy. There's no way I'd have dipped my toe in it.\"{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Post-swimming activities==\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Dawn Fraser\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AC|MBE}}\n|constituency_MP  = [[Electoral district of Balmain|Balmain]]\n|parliament       = New South Wales\n|term_start       = 19 March 1988\n|term_end         = 25 May 1991\n|predecessor      = [[Peter Crawford (Australian politician)|Peter Crawford]]\n|successor        = District abolished\n}}\nFraser became a publican at the [[Balmain, New South Wales#Drinking establishments|Riverview Hotel]], Balmain, and took up swimming coaching. In 1988, she was elected as an [[independent politician|independent]] to the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Electoral district of Balmain|seat of Balmain]]. That electorate was abolished in 1991, and after she failed to win the new seat of [[Electoral district of Port Jackson|Port Jackson]], she retired from politics.<ref name=r1/><ref name=\"Dawn Fraser NSW Parl\">{{Cite NSW Parliament |id=1947 |former=Yes |access-date=13 May 2019 |title=Ms Dawn Fraser (1937\u2013 ) }}</ref>\nFraser is a high-profile supporter and a board director of the [[Wests Tigers]] [[NRL]] club.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/benji-marshall-good-natured-dawn-fraser/story-fn3dxity-1226121182177</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nShe was named the [[Australian of the Year]] in 1964,<ref>{{cite book | author=Lewis, Wendy | title=Australians of the Year | publisher=Pier 9 Press | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-74196-809-5 | authorlink=Wendy Lewis }}</ref> was inducted into the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] in 1965,<ref name=ishofprofile>International Swimming Hall of Fame, Honorees, [http://www.ishof.org/dawn-fraser-(aus).html  Dawn Fraser (AUS)].  Retrieved 17 March 2015.</ref> was made a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1967,<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1088356&search_type=advanced&showInd=true It's an Honour] \u2013 Member of the Order of the British Empire</ref> and appointed an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO) in 1998.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=872625&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] \u2013 Officer of the Order of Australia</ref>  Also in 1998, she was voted Australia's greatest female athlete in history.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}  She was named Australian Female Athlete of the Century by the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]],<ref name=\"smh2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/fraser-named-greatest-despite-push-for-skater-20130227-2f6dm.html|title=Fraser named greatest despite push for skater|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=28 February 2013|first=Chris|last=Wilson|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> who had inducted her as their first female member in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=79&memberType=legends|title=Dawn Fraser AO MBE|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>  In 1999 the [[International Olympic Committee]] named her the World's Greatest Living Female Water Sports Champion.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} on 14 July 2000, Fraser was awarded the [[Australian Sports Medal]] for \"outstanding contribution as a swimming competitor\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Dawn Fraser|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=980531&search_type=simple&showInd=true|publisher=Australian Honours Database|accessdate=8 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of the bearers of the [[Olympic Torch]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]] of the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney. She carried the Olympic Torch at the stadium, as one of the bearers for the final segment, before the lighting of the [[Olympic Flame]].\n\nThe [[Australian Sport Awards]] includes an award named in honour of and presented by Fraser. The sea baths in Balmain where she swam were named the [[Dawn Fraser Swimming Pool]] in her honour in 1964,<ref>http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/visit/ViewAttractionDetail.aspx?ID=5001040#</ref> and in 1992, the [[State Transit Authority]] named a [[Sydney RiverCats|RiverCat ferry]] after Fraser.\n\nAs part of the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)|2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]] she was advanced to a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/2001256 |title=FRASER, Dawn |work=It's An Honour |publisher=Australian Government |date=11 June 2018 |accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In film==\nIn 1979, a movie called ''[[Dawn!]]'' was made about Fraser's life and career. It starred Bronwyn Mackay-Payne as Fraser.\n\nFraser was played by [[Melissa Thomas]] in the 2003 film ''[[Swimming Upstream]]''. Fraser herself is credited in the film as Dawn Fraser's coach.\nOn  1 September 2015, Dawn Fraser featured on Season 7, Episode 5 of the [[SBS (Australian TV channel)|SBS]] genealogy television series [[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]], which traced her heritage back to South America.\n\n== Personal life ==\nFraser married Gary Ware on 30 January 1965 at St Stephens Church, Macquarie Street, Sydney.<ref name=sl-pic-wedding>{{cite web |last1=Hickson|first1=Jack |title=Dawn Fraser's wedding to Gary Ware, St. Stephen's Church, Sydney |url=http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/item/itemDetailPaged.aspx?itemID=98512 |website=acms.sl.nsw.gov.au |date=30 January 1965 |publisher=State Library of NSW |accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The marriage was short-lived. She has one daughter from the marriage, Dawn-Lorraine, who has a son, Jackson. Dawn Fraser suffered from severe asthma.<ref name=abc-kicking>{{cite interview|author=Fraser, Dawn|interviewer=Attard, Monica|title=Dawn Fraser: still kicking|url=http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|website=Sunday Profile www.abc.net.a|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=21 December 2014|date=15 April  2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212085422/http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1897086.htm|archive-date=12 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=smh-smiling>{{cite news |last1=Hardy|first1=Karen |title=Dawn Fraser still smiling |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/dawn-fraser-still-smiling-20131213-2zarg.html |accessdate=21 December 2014 |work=The Sydney Morining Herald |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFraser has drawn negative criticism for public comments in 1997 when she said \"I'm sick and tired of the immigrants that are coming into my country\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/from-olympic-bans-to-one-nation-dawn-fraser-no-stranger-to-controversy-20150707-gi6sgw.html#ixzz3kkQ1HLXL|title=From Olympic bans to One Nation: Dawn Fraser no stranger to controversy|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> and in 2015 when she told Australian tennis players [[Nick Kyrgios]] and [[Bernard Tomic]] to \"go back to where their fathers or parents came from\u201d. \"I've always spoken the truth,\" Fraser said. \"It was the way I was brought up, to be honest and to tell the truth.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/> These views have been described as racist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/tennis/olympic-legend-dawn-fraser-launches-racist-attack-on-nick-kyrgios/story-fnu2pjj2-1227431907759|title=Dawn Fraser attacks Nick Kyrgios after Wimbledon 2015 loss|date=7 July 2015|work=NewsComAu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/dawn-frasers-comments-about-kyrgios-and-tomic-were-racist-say-experts-20150707-gi70b6.html |title=Dawn Fraser's comments about Kyrgios and Tomic were racist, say experts |first1=Angus |last1=Holland |date=July 7, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |access-date=August 13, 2016 }}</ref> She subsequently apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jul/07/dawn-fraser-sorry-for-racist-outburst-on-nick-kyrgios-and-bernard-tomic |title=Dawn Fraser sorry for 'racist' outburst on Nick Kyrgios and Bernard Tomic |date=July 7, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=August 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Olympic accomplishments==\n[[File:Dawn Fraser 1958.jpg|thumb|Dawn Fraser in 1958]]\n[[File:Dawn Fraser and Ilsa Konrads at the Australian National Swimming Championships and Olympic Trials, North Sydney Olympic Pool, 27 February 1960.jpeg|thumb|Dawn Fraser and Ilsa Konrads at the Australian National Swimming Championships and Olympic Trials, North Sydney Olympic Pool, 27 February 1960]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| '''Event'''\n| align=\"center\" | '''Time'''\n| align=\"center\" | '''Place'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1956 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 1:02.0\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"00CC33\" align=\"center\" | '''WR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 5:02.5\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:17.1\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"00CC33\" align=\"center\" | '''WR'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1960 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 1:01.2\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"orange\" align=\"center\" | '''OR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 4:58.5\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 5th\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:11.3\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Medley Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:45.9\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |  1964 Summer Olympics\n|-\n|  100m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 59.5\n| bgcolor=\"Gold\" align=\"center\" | '''Gold''' ||bgcolor=\"orange\" align=\"center\" | '''OR'''\n|-\n|  400m Freestyle|| align=\"center\" | 4:47.6\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 4th\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:06.9\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\" | '''Silver'''\n|-\n|  4 \u00d7 100 m Medley Relay|| align=\"center\" | 4:52.3\n| bgcolor=\"white\" align=\"center\" | 9th\n|}\n\n*[[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1962 Perth Commonwealth Games]]\n**110&nbsp;yards freestyle \u2013 gold medal\n**440&nbsp;yards freestyle \u2013 gold medal\n**4 x 110&nbsp;yards (4 x 100.58 metres) freestyle relay \u2013 gold medal\n**4 x 110&nbsp;yards (4 x 100.58 metres) medley relay \u2013 gold medal\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of members of the International Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (women)]]\n* [[World record progression 100 metres freestyle]]\n* [[World record progression 200 metres freestyle]]\n* [[World record progression 4 \u00d7 100 metres freestyle relay]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.olympics.com.au/athletes.cfm?AthleteID=2209 Dawn Fraser] &ndash; Olympic athlete profile at Australian Olympic Committee\n* [http://www.dawnfraser.com.au/records.htm Dawn Fraser's world records]\n* [http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0386b.htm  Dawn Fraser] &ndash; article in ''The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia''\n* [http://www.ishof.org/dawn-fraser-(aus).html  Dawn Fraser (AUS)] &ndash; Honor Swimmer profile at International Swimming Hall of Fame\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Peter Crawford (Australian politician)|Peter Crawford]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = Member for [[Electoral district of Balmain|Balmain]] | years=1988&ndash;1991}}\n{{s-non | reason= District abolished }}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Willy den Ouden ]]|title=[[World record progression 100 metres freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle<br>world record holder (long course)]]|years=21 February 1956 \u2013 3 March 1956|after=[[Cocky Gastelaars]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Cocky Gastelaars]]|title=[[World record progression 100 metres freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle<br>world record holder (long course)]]|years=25 August 1956 \u2013 20 October 1956|after=[[Lorraine Crapp]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 100 m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 4x100 m Freestyle Relay Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 100m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 400m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 4x100m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Associated Press Female Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{Australians of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraser, Dawn}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Female freestyle swimmers]]\n[[Category:Australian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:World record setters in swimming]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the Parliament of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Australian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:Sport Australia Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]