{"title_page": "Melbourne Star", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Melbourne Star\n|former_names       = Southern Star<ref name=onlymelbourne12219>{{Cite web|url=http://www.onlymelbourne.com.au/melbourne_details.php?id=12219|title=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel|work=Only Melbourne|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n|image              = Melbourne Star Observation Wheel.jpg\n|caption            = Melbourne Star in December 2013\n|status             = Operational \n|building_type      = [[Ferris wheel]]\n|location           = [[Docklands, Victoria|Melbourne Docklands]], Australia\n|coordinates        = {{coord|-37.8110723|144.9368763|region:AU|display=inline,title}}\n|start_date         = 30 June 2006<ref name=heraldsun300506>{{Cite news|url = http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,19300554-2862,00.html|title=Work to spin Ferris wheel|publisher=Herald Sun|date=30 May 2006|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n|opened_date        = Original wheel: 20 December 2008<ref name=theage191208>{{Cite news|last=Rennie|first=Reko|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=After the spin, Melbourne's wheel ready to turn|date=19 December 2008|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/after-the-spin-melbournes-wheel-ready-to-turn-20081219-721z.html|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref><br />Replacement wheel: 23 December 2013<ref>{{cite web|last=Minear|first=Tom|title=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel spins back into action|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-spins-back-into-action/story-fni0fit3-1226788374973|publisher=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=23 December 2013|date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n|cost               = [[Australian dollar|A$]]100 million (estimate)<ref name=heraldsun201008>{{Cite news|last1=Royall|first1=Ian|last2=Johnston|first2=Matt|publisher=[[Herald Sun]]|title=Man seeks to propose to girlfriend in new Southern Star wheel|date =20 October 2008|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/a-wheel-big-turn-on/story-e6frf7jo-1111117795297|accessdate=25 October 2008}}</ref>\n|owner              = [[Sanoyas Hishino Meisho|Sanoyas Rides Australia Pty. Ltd.]]<ref>[http://www.sanoyas.co.jp/en/ridesa/corporate/index.html Greetings | Our Company | Sanoyas Rides Australia Pty Ltd]</ref>\n|height             = {{Convert|120|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=theage191208/>\n|architect          = Sanoyas<ref name=theage111013>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/melbourne-star-bought-by-its-japanese-builder-20131011-2vdb2.html|title=Melbourne Star bought by its Japanese builder|author=Stephen Cauchi|publisher=The Age|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013}}</ref>\n|main_contractor    = [[Hansen Yuncken]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Southern Star|publisher=The Southern Star|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/|accessdate=1 July 2008}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Melbourne Star''' (previously '''Southern Star''') is a giant [[Ferris wheel]]<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS from 'Ferris wheel' to 'observation wheel' without first establishing a clear consensus on the Talk: page. Changes made here without clear consensus are always reverted. --> in the [[Docklands, Victoria#Waterfront City|Waterfront City]] precinct in the [[Docklands, Victoria|Docklands area]] of [[Melbourne]], the state capital of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]].\n\nDescribed by its operators as \"the Southern Hemisphere's only giant observation wheel\",<ref>{{Cite web|title=Melbourne Star|publisher=Melbourne Star|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us.html|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref> it is {{Convert|120|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} tall and has seven spokes, reflecting the seven-pointed star of the Australian flag.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.docklandsnews.com.au/columns/detail/docklands-science-march-2013_8432/|title=Docklands Science|publisher=Docklands News|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt opened two years behind schedule in December 2008, but closed 40 days later due to structural defects, and was subsequently dismantled for major repairs. The wheel itself was scrapped and replaced, but the original support structure and passenger cabins were retained. It was originally thought that reconstruction might be completed in late 2010, but repeated delays meant it did not reopen until 23 December 2013.\n\nA ride (one complete rotation) takes 30 minutes and, according to the Star's website, provides uninterrupted 360-degree views of up to {{Convert|40|km}} \"encompassing the Docklands precinct, Melbourne\u2019s CBD, Port Phillip Bay and as far as Mount Macedon, Arthur\u2019s Seat and the Dandenong Ranges.\"<ref name=melbournestar061213>{{Cite web|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us/news/melbourne-star-confirms-late-december-opening-family-tickets-to-be-offered.html|title=Melbourne Star news|date=6 December 2013|website=Melbourne Star|publisher=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==2006\u20132009==\n\n===Construction===\nThe project was undertaken by [[ING Group|ING Real Estate]] and the construction consultant was [[Hansen Yuncken]]. The wheel was designed and built by Sanoyas Rides Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of the Japanese ship and amusement park ride builder [[Sanoyas Hishino Meisho|Sanoyas Holdings Corporation]], and the steel builder was Alfasi Steel Constructions.<ref name=theage111013/><ref name=theage261209>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/yearlong-wait-as-scrapped-wheel-is-rebuilt-20091226-lfqa.html|title=Year-long wait as scrapped wheel is rebuilt|publisher=The Age|date=27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nConstruction began in 2006.<ref name=theage111013/> By 1 March 2008 the outer rim had been completed,<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/look-at-me-im-a-big-wheel-now/story-e6frf7kx-1111115683016 Look at me, I'm a big wheel now]</ref> and by 21 October air-conditioned enclosed passenger cabins, built in Osaka, Japan,<ref name=heraldsun300506/> were receiving their fit out.<ref name=heraldsun201008/> Each cabin weighs 13 tonnes, is {{Convert|5.7|m|abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|3.7|m|abbr=on}} high, has floor to ceiling glass walls, and can accommodate up to 20 passengers.<ref name=theage280813>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/longdelayed-milestone-for-docklands-wheel-as-first-cabin-attached-20130828-2spji.html|title=Long-delayed milestone for Docklands wheel as first cabin attached|publisher=The Age|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Southern Star Observation Wheel |publisher=The Southern Star |url=http://www.waterfrontcity.com.au/Home/tabid/56/mid/465/newsid465/40/Default.aspx |date=28 April 2008 |accessdate=13 March 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719084801/http://www.waterfrontcity.com.au/Home/tabid/56/mid/465/newsid465/40/Default.aspx |archivedate=19 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n[[File:Southern Star Complete.jpg|thumb|Southern Star prior to its 2009 closure]]\n[[File:The Southern Star Twisted Metal.jpg|thumb|Failed joint from the 2009 wheel]]\n\nThe wheel first opened to the public on 20 December 2008,<ref name=theage191208/> two years behind schedule.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://designbuildsource.com.au/opening-date-for-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-mark-2-imminent|title=Opening Date For Melbourne\u2019s Southern Star Wheel (Mark 2) Imminent|publisher=DesignBuildSource|date=8 March 2013|access-date=8 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311133502/http://designbuildsource.com.au/opening-date-for-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-mark-2-imminent|archive-date=11 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Its most recently postponed opening ceremony, scheduled for 28 November 2008,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rennie|first=Reko|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=Melbourne's big wheel to open next month|date=27 October 2008|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/10/27/1224955915134.html|accessdate=27 October 2008}}</ref> had been cancelled due to bad weather and delays in procuring parts.<ref name=theage191208/> It had cost an estimated [[Australian dollar|A$]]100 million to construct and was expected to attract more than one million visitors annually. Tickets cost A$29 for adults and A$17 for children.<ref name=heraldsun201008/> As at 2018 adult tickets cost A$39 for adults and A$27 for children\n\n===Closure===\nOn 30 January 2009,<ref name=theage020209>{{Cite news|title=Heat Closes Melbourne's Southern Star|publisher=The Age|date=2 February 2009|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/heat-closes-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-20090202-7v8r.html|accessdate=2 February 2009|first=Mex|last=Cooper}}</ref> 40 days after opening,<ref name=heraldsun062012>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/m-southern-star-observation-wheel-a-broken-wreck-and-lord-mayor-robert-doyle-is-just-sick-of-it/story-fn7x8me2-1226391611329|title=$100m Southern Star Observation Wheel a broken wreck|work=Herald Sun|date=13 June 2012}}</ref> the wheel was shut down by [[WorkSafe Victoria|WorkSafe]] after cracks up to three metres ({{Convert|3|m|ft|disp=out}}) long were inadvertently discovered by a contract worker installing LED lighting. One node was almost completely torn from its welded joint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/huge-cracks-in-wheel-of-misfortune-20090704-d8hj.html|title=Huge cracks in wheel of misfortune|last1=Houston|first1=Cameron|date=5 July 2009|publisher=The Age|accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> Initially the operators blamed the [[Early 2009 southeastern Australia heat wave|2009 Southeastern Australia heat wave]] for causing the damage and it was not known when the wheel would reopen.<ref name=theage020209/>\n\nUpon further investigation, engineers working on the wheel discovered the cracks were not caused by the heatwave but rather a problem in the original design. Fourteen cracks were found in the steel.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Design fault to keep wheel shut|publisher=The Age|date=2 March 2009|url=http://business.theage.com.au/business/design-fault-to-keep-ailing-wheel-shut-20090301-8lh8.html|accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn undated press release on the operator's official website stated: \"The Southern Star Observation Wheel was temporarily closed in January 2009. As a result of extensive design and technical reviews a conclusion was reached to build a new wheel.\"<ref name=onlymelbourne12219/><!-- original sources thesouthernstar.com.au/mediarelease.aspx?id=19 & thesouthernstar.com.au/MediaCentre.aspx no longer available -->\n\nSanoyas, who designed and built the wheel, accepted responsibility for the cracks and undertook its reconstruction under warranty. Consulting engineers Arup, steel builder Alfasi, and construction consultant Hansen Yuncken signed confidentiality agreements preventing them from commenting publicly. Most of the original wheel was sold for scrap, but the main support columns and the passenger cabins were retained and reused.<ref name=theage261209/>\n\nThe reconstruction process began in a factory in [[Dandenong South, Victoria|South Dandenong]] in December 2009, at which time it was expected that a year would pass before the wheel would reopen.<ref name=theage261209/>\n\n==2010==\nIn October it was reported that the viability of the wheel was in doubt after contractors stopped work because they had not been paid, although a spokeswoman for Southern Star Management Group denied this, stating that \"the construction process is extremely intricate and highly influenced by adverse weather conditions, including rain, wind, [and] hot and cold weather[.]\"<ref>[http://m.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/work-grinds-to-halt-on-southern-star-observation-wheel/story-e6frf7kx-1225934564252 Work grinds to halt on Southern Star Observation Wheel]</ref>\n\n==2011==\nIn January the first of the seven replacement spokes, manufactured by BMC in the [[Latrobe Valley]], was delivered to Docklands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad/observation-wheel-at-a-turning-point/story-fn6bfkm6-1225985227901|title=Observation wheel at a turning point|publisher=Herald Sun|date=11 January 2011}}</ref> In July the wheel was expected to be turning again by the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad/docklands-attraction-making-wheel-progress/story-fn6bfmgc-1226105063728|title=Docklands attraction making wheel progress|publisher=Herald Sun|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 November reconstruction work was in progress when the wheel broke free from its restraints and began turning in strong winds, resulting in minor injuries for one of the workers as they fled the site. The next day, Southern Star Management issued a statement saying that bracing used to erect the wheel had failed, and that no final completion date for the wheel had yet been confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/more-news/more-trouble-hits-southern-star-observation-wheel/story-fn7x8me2-1226208890059|title=Union blames Government for Southern Star Observation Wheel accident|publisher=Herald Sun|date=29 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-11-29/more-trouble-for-dockands-observation-wheel/3701980|title=More trouble for Docklands observation wheel|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> In December it was reported that the wheel was not expected to reopen before Easter 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/wheels-safety-in-doubt-union-20111204-1odk0.html|title=Wheel's safety in doubt: union|publisher=The Age|date=5 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==2012==\nIn January it was reported that an international team of experts including [[Arup Group Limited|Arup]] (who were involved in both the [[London Eye]] and the [[Singapore Flyer]] projects) and [[Hyder Consulting]] had been engaged in the redesign, and that reconstruction was now expected to be completed before the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smartplanet.com/blog/global-observer/melbournes-big-wheel-of-misfortune/3479|title=Melbourne's big wheel of misfortune|publisher=Smart Planet|date=28 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2012/01/melbournes-southern-star-wheel-to-get-\u2018world-first-led-lighting-system\u2019/|title=Melbourne's Southern Star Wheel To Get 'World First LED Lighting System'|publisher=Gizmodo|date=30 January 2012}}</ref> In June it was reported that the then owner ING Real Estate had repeatedly refused to announce an estimated completion date, but that an estimated date might be given at a briefing of state government officials planned for July.<ref name=heraldsun062012/>\n\nIn August it was reported that the wheel could reopen in January 2013, but only if there was \"no wind, no rain for the next four months\" \u2013 an unlikely scenario for Melbourne, \"a city renowned for extremely windy springs and rain that washes out the first cricket matches\". According to spokesman Ken Davis, 70 per cent of available construction time was being lost each week as cranes and lifts on the site could not operate in bad weather. He also stated that \"due to the complexity of the construction process, we are not in a position to make any announcements regarding a 2013 opening date\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/wheels-misfortune-continues-and-traders-are-not-happy-20121008-2784u.html|title=Wheel's misfortune continues, and traders are not happy|publisher=The Age|date=8 October 2012}}</ref> However, later that same month, after the final section of the rim was installed, he stated \"we're hoping it will be completed by the middle of next year\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/circle-complete-as-southern-star-reinvents-the-wheel-20121018-27t9p.html|title=Circle complete as Southern Star reinvents the wheel|publisher=The Age|date=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2013==\nIn January, ING Real Estate advised that the wheel would not reopen until the second half of the year,<ref name=\"Timing\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/wheels-reopening-at-least-six-months-away-20130122-2d4sg.html|title=Wheel's reopening at least six months away|publisher=The Age|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref> and on 27 April it was renamed as the Melbourne Star.<!--[[NOTE: Have dated the name change, 27 April 2013, based on an email from the PR firm for the wheel, who advised me that the name change took place on 27 April 2013. Not sure how to provide a reference for that as it is an email to me, not a public document. The PR person advised they did not issue a press release for the name change.]]--> On 25 August the opening was put back yet again, to March 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/docklands-traders-in-spin-over-1800-day-wait-for-melbourne-star-wheel-fix/story-fni0fit3-1226703753763|title=Docklands traders in spin over 1800-day wait for Melbourne Star wheel fix|publisher=Herald Sun 25 August 2013|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Three days later the first of the original cabins, which had been in storage since the original wheel was dismantled, was reinstalled. This took up to three-quarters of a day each, depending on weather conditions. The only substantial modification was an upgrade of their audio systems.<ref name=theage280813/>\n\n[[File:Melbourne Star August 2013 1.JPG|thumb|left|The first cars being reattached during the restoration in August 2013]]\nOn 11 October it was announced that Sanoyas had purchased the wheel from ING Real Estate for an undisclosed price, and that Melbourne Star Management Group would continue to manage it.<ref name=theage111013/><ref name=heraldsun111013>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/japanese-breathe-new-life-into-docklands-ferris-wheel-project/story-fni0fit3-1226738512996|title=Japanese breathe new life into Docklands ferris wheel project|publisher=Herald Sun|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> On 25 October, Sanoyas Holdings Corporation president Takashi Ueda announced that the company was aiming to reopen the attraction in ten weeks time. Advertisements for approximately 100 jobs began appearing on the Melbourne Star website and on the 'SEEK' recruiting website.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/docklands-troubleplagued-observation-wheel-set-to-open-in-ten-weeks/story-fni0fiyv-1226746281272|title=Docklands' trouble-plagued observation wheel set to open in ten weeks|publisher=Herald Sun|date=25 October 2013|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Reopening===\n[[File:Melbourne Star Observation Wheel 17th Dec 2013.jpg|thumb|Original passenger cabins fitted to the new wheel]]\nOn 6 December 2013 it was reported that construction work had been completed,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-06/southern-star-observation-wheel-set-to-reopen-soon/5139856|title=Melbourne Star observation wheel set to reopen soon, pending final tests|work=ABC News|date=6 December 2013}}</ref> and an announcement on the Star's website stated that the reopening would be in late December. Melbourne Star Management Group CEO Chris Kelly was quoted as saying \"We are working to the earliest possible opening date. We are now well into the commissioning process, which is the final stage before opening, but some activities do remain weather dependent.\"<ref name=melbournestar061213/>\n\nOn 15 December a promotional television advertising campaign commenced, and three days later it was announced that \"The Melbourne Star Observation Wheel will open for guests at 12 noon on Monday, December 23, 2013\"<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Melbourne Star advertisement |episodelink= |url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us/news.html |accessdate= |series= |serieslink= |first= |last= |network=Nine Network & Seven Network |station=Nine Melbourne and Seven Melbourne |location=Melbourne |date=15 December 2013 |began= |ended= |season= |seriesno= |number= |time=2pm & 9.11pm (0.5 minutes) |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> \u2013 almost five years after the original wheel was shut down in January 2009.<ref name=newscomau181213>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-reopens-after-five-years-in-time-for-christmas-holidays/story-fnii5sms-1226785614507|title=Melbourne's observation wheel opens next week|last1=Masanauskas|first1=John|date=18 December 2013|website=News|publisher=News Ltd|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 26 December, three days after the reopening, the wheel was stopped for several minutes while a cabin was inspected and taken out of service after passenger Marco Bresciani discovered a cracked window. CEO Chris Kelly described the damage as a \"very minor cosmetic issue\" caused by a bird strike. \"The glass has been inspected and our advice is that it is cosmetic and doesn't present any safety issues. It is in the process of being repaired.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/bird-strike-cause-of-crack-on-melbourne-star-observation-wheel-pod-window/story-fni0fit3-1226791565537 |title=Bird strike cause of crack on Melbourne Star Observation Wheel pod window  |last1=Mickelburough |first1=Peter |last2= |first2= |date=29 December 2013 |website=Herald Sun |publisher=News Ltd |accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the afternoon of 28 December the wheel was evacuated to allow a \"full inspection\" after the wheel unexpectedly stopped rotating. It was restarted 15 minutes later. Spokeswoman Sally Abbott said technicians had identified an \"isolated incident\" but refused to provide any details.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-spins-into-trouble-again/story-fni0fit3-1226791190469 Melbourne Star Observation Wheel spins into trouble again]</ref>\n\nThe [[Victorian Workcover Authority]] subsequently investigated safety complaints by several visitors.<ref name=heraldsu1226793373976>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/worksafe-to-probe-melbourne-star-observation-wheel/story-fni0fit3-1226793373976 WorkSafe to probe Melbourne Star Observation Wheel]</ref> Two families were reported to have been traumatised and left \"shaking and in tears\" after cabin eight became stuck and began tilting as the wheel turned. The operators confirmed that an alarm was triggered on both occasions but refused to say what triggered it, whether the two incidents were connected, if the same cabin was involved, if cabin eight remained in service, or whether it had been serviced between the two incidents. CEO Chris Kelly said the wheel remained open and safe for tourists even though one of the cabins had been taken out of service, and insisted that the cabin \"did not tilt or rock at any stage\". He refused to answer questions about the mechanics of the wheel or the cabins, or to confirm that the same cabin was involved in both incidents, saying: \"It is not our policy to comment on the specifics due to the highly complex engineering and electrical systems that operate the Star\" and \"It is not our policy to divulge this information as we don't want people to needlessly avoid specific cabins in the future.\"<ref name=heraldsu1226793373976/><ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-cabin-out-of-action-amid-worksafe-probe-20140102-306lj.html Melbourne Star Observation Wheel cabin out of action amid WorkSafe probe]</ref><ref>[http://heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-pod-fails-to-keep-level-says-family/story-fni0fit3-1226792674705 Melbourne Star Observation Wheel pod fails to keep level, says family]</ref>\n\n==2014==\n[[File:Aerial perspective of the Melbourne Star Observation Wheel.jpg|thumb|Melbourne Star, 2017]]\n\nOn 24 January the Star was again unexpectedly closed. Visitors arriving at the wheel were told the closure was due to \"windy conditions\", however a spokeswoman said \"operations have been temporarily suspended due to a software problem. Our technical services team are undertaking a comprehensive investigation to identify and correct the issue and we are expecting to resume operations later today.\"<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/travel/travel-incidents/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-halted-again-20140124-31dem.html Troubled wheel halted again]</ref> The wheel was closed from 11:00 until the following morning.<ref>[http://theaustralian.com.au/news/melbournes-docklands-observation-wheel-reopens-after-software-glitch/story-e6frg6n6-1226809701142 Melbourne's Docklands observation wheel reopens after software glitch]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Melbourne Star}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.melbournestar.com}}\n\n{{Ferris wheel}}\n{{Melbourne landmarks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melbourne Star}}\n[[Category:Ferris wheels in Australia]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Melbourne Star\n|former_names       = Southern Star<ref name=onlymelbourne12219>{{Cite web|url=http://www.onlymelbourne.com.au/melbourne_details.php?id=12219|title=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel|work=Only Melbourne|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n|image              = Melbourne Star Observation Wheel.jpg\n|caption            = Melbourne Star in December 2013\n|status             = Operational \n|building_type      = [[Ferris wheel]]\n|location           = [[Docklands, Victoria|Melbourne Docklands]], Australia\n|coordinates        = {{coord|-37.8110723|144.9368763|region:AU|display=inline,title}}\n|start_date         = 30 June 2006<ref name=heraldsun300506>{{Cite news|url = http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,19300554-2862,00.html|title=Work to spin Ferris wheel|publisher=Herald Sun|date=30 May 2006|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n|opened_date        = Original wheel: 20 December 2008<ref name=theage191208>{{Cite news|last=Rennie|first=Reko|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=After the spin, Melbourne's wheel ready to turn|date=19 December 2008|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/after-the-spin-melbournes-wheel-ready-to-turn-20081219-721z.html|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref><br />Replacement wheel: 23 December 2013<ref>{{cite web|last=Minear|first=Tom|title=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel spins back into action|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-spins-back-into-action/story-fni0fit3-1226788374973|publisher=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=23 December 2013|date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n|cost               = [[Australian dollar|A$]]100 million (estimate)<ref name=heraldsun201008>{{Cite news|last1=Royall|first1=Ian|last2=Johnston|first2=Matt|publisher=[[Herald Sun]]|title=Man seeks to propose to girlfriend in new Southern Star wheel|date =20 October 2008|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/a-wheel-big-turn-on/story-e6frf7jo-1111117795297|accessdate=25 October 2008}}</ref>\n|owner              = [[Sanoyas Hishino Meisho|Sanoyas Rides Australia Pty. Ltd.]]<ref>[http://www.sanoyas.co.jp/en/ridesa/corporate/index.html Greetings | Our Company | Sanoyas Rides Australia Pty Ltd]</ref>\n|height             = {{Convert|120|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=theage191208/>\n|architect          = Sanoyas<ref name=theage111013>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/melbourne-star-bought-by-its-japanese-builder-20131011-2vdb2.html|title=Melbourne Star bought by its Japanese builder|author=Stephen Cauchi|publisher=The Age|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013}}</ref>\n|main_contractor    = [[Hansen Yuncken]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Southern Star|publisher=The Southern Star|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/|accessdate=1 July 2008}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Melbourne Star''' (previously '''Southern Star''') is a giant [[Ferris wheel]]<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS from 'Ferris wheel' to 'observation wheel' without first establishing a clear consensus on the Talk: page. Changes made here without clear consensus are always reverted. --> in the [[Docklands, Victoria#Waterfront City|Waterfront City]] precinct in the [[Docklands, Victoria|Docklands area]] of [[Melbourne]], the state capital of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]].\n\nDescribed by its operators as \"the Southern Hemisphere's only giant observation wheel\",<ref>{{Cite web|title=Melbourne Star|publisher=Melbourne Star|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us.html|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref> it is {{Convert|120|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} tall and has seven spokes, reflecting the seven-pointed star of the Australian flag.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.docklandsnews.com.au/columns/detail/docklands-science-march-2013_8432/|title=Docklands Science|publisher=Docklands News|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt opened two years behind schedule in December 2008, but closed 40 days later due to structural defects, and was subsequently dismantled for major repairs. The wheel itself was scrapped and replaced, but the original support structure and passenger cabins were retained. It was originally thought that reconstruction might be completed in late 2010, but repeated delays meant it did not reopen until 23 December 2013.\n\nA ride (one complete rotation) takes 30 minutes and, according to the Star's website, provides uninterrupted 360-degree views of up to {{Convert|40|km}} \"encompassing the Docklands precinct, Melbourne\u2019s CBD, Port Phillip Bay and as far as Mount Macedon, Arthur\u2019s Seat and the Dandenong Ranges.\"<ref name=melbournestar061213>{{Cite web|url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us/news/melbourne-star-confirms-late-december-opening-family-tickets-to-be-offered.html|title=Melbourne Star news|date=6 December 2013|website=Melbourne Star|publisher=Melbourne Star Observation Wheel|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==2006-2009==\n\n===Construction===\nThe project was undertaken by [[ING Group|ING Real Estate]] and the construction consultant was [[Hansen Yuncken]]. The wheel was designed and built by Sanoyas Rides Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of the Japanese ship and amusement park ride builder [[Sanoyas Hishino Meisho|Sanoyas Holdings Corporation]], and the steel builder was Alfasi Steel Constructions.<ref name=theage111013/><ref name=theage261209>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/yearlong-wait-as-scrapped-wheel-is-rebuilt-20091226-lfqa.html|title=Year-long wait as scrapped wheel is rebuilt|publisher=The Age|date=27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nConstruction began in 2006.<ref name=theage111013/> By 1 March 2008 the outer rim had been completed,<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/look-at-me-im-a-big-wheel-now/story-e6frf7kx-1111115683016 Look at me, I'm a big wheel now]</ref> and by 21 October air-conditioned enclosed passenger cabins, built in Osaka, Japan,<ref name=heraldsun300506/> were receiving their fit out.<ref name=heraldsun201008/> Each cabin weighs 13 tonnes, is {{Convert|5.7|m|abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|3.7|m|abbr=on}} high, has floor to ceiling glass walls, and can accommodate up to 20 passengers.<ref name=theage280813>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/longdelayed-milestone-for-docklands-wheel-as-first-cabin-attached-20130828-2spji.html|title=Long-delayed milestone for Docklands wheel as first cabin attached|publisher=The Age|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Southern Star Observation Wheel |publisher=The Southern Star |url=http://www.waterfrontcity.com.au/Home/tabid/56/mid/465/newsid465/40/Default.aspx |date=28 April 2008 |accessdate=13 March 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719084801/http://www.waterfrontcity.com.au/Home/tabid/56/mid/465/newsid465/40/Default.aspx |archivedate=19 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n[[File:Southern Star Complete.jpg|thumb|Southern Star prior to its 2009 closure]]\n[[File:The Southern Star Twisted Metal.jpg|thumb|Failed joint from the 2009 wheel]]\n\nThe wheel first opened to the public on 20 December 2008,<ref name=theage191208/> two years behind schedule.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://designbuildsource.com.au/opening-date-for-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-mark-2-imminent|title=Opening Date For Melbourne\u2019s Southern Star Wheel (Mark 2) Imminent|publisher=DesignBuildSource|date=8 March 2013|access-date=8 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311133502/http://designbuildsource.com.au/opening-date-for-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-mark-2-imminent|archive-date=11 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Its most recently postponed opening ceremony, scheduled for 28 November 2008,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rennie|first=Reko|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=Melbourne's big wheel to open next month|date=27 October 2008|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/10/27/1224955915134.html|accessdate=27 October 2008}}</ref> had been cancelled due to bad weather and delays in procuring parts.<ref name=theage191208/> It had cost an estimated [[Australian dollar|A$]]100 million to construct and was expected to attract more than one million visitors annually. Tickets cost A$29 for adults and A$17 for children.<ref name=heraldsun201008/> As at 2018 adult tickets cost A$39 for adults and A$27 for children\n\n===Closure===\nOn 30 January 2009,<ref name=theage020209>{{Cite news|title=Heat Closes Melbourne's Southern Star|publisher=The Age|date=2 February 2009|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/heat-closes-melbournes-southern-star-wheel-20090202-7v8r.html|accessdate=2 February 2009|first=Mex|last=Cooper}}</ref> 40 days after opening,<ref name=heraldsun062012>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/m-southern-star-observation-wheel-a-broken-wreck-and-lord-mayor-robert-doyle-is-just-sick-of-it/story-fn7x8me2-1226391611329|title=$100m Southern Star Observation Wheel a broken wreck|work=Herald Sun|date=13 June 2012}}</ref> the wheel was shut down by [[WorkSafe Victoria|WorkSafe]] after cracks up to three metres ({{Convert|3|m|ft|disp=out}}) long were inadvertently discovered by a contract worker installing LED lighting. One node was almost completely torn from its welded joint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/huge-cracks-in-wheel-of-misfortune-20090704-d8hj.html|title=Huge cracks in wheel of misfortune|last1=Houston|first1=Cameron|date=5 July 2009|publisher=The Age|accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> Initially the operators blamed the [[Early 2009 southeastern Australia heat wave|2009 Southeastern Australia heat wave]] for causing the damage and it was not known when the wheel would reopen.<ref name=theage020209/>\n\nUpon further investigation, engineers working on the wheel discovered the cracks were not caused by the heatwave but rather a problem in the original design. Fourteen cracks were found in the steel.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Design fault to keep wheel shut|publisher=The Age|date=2 March 2009|url=http://business.theage.com.au/business/design-fault-to-keep-ailing-wheel-shut-20090301-8lh8.html|accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn undated press release on the operator's official website stated: \"The Southern Star Observation Wheel was temporarily closed in January 2009. As a result of extensive design and technical reviews a conclusion was reached to build a new wheel.\"<ref name=onlymelbourne12219/><!-- original sources thesouthernstar.com.au/mediarelease.aspx?id=19 & thesouthernstar.com.au/MediaCentre.aspx no longer available -->\n\nSanoyas, who designed and built the wheel, accepted responsibility for the cracks and undertook its reconstruction under warranty. Consulting engineers Arup, steel builder Alfasi, and construction consultant Hansen Yuncken signed confidentiality agreements preventing them from commenting publicly. Most of the original wheel was sold for scrap, but the main support columns and the passenger cabins were retained and reused.<ref name=theage261209/>\n\nThe reconstruction process began in a factory in [[Dandenong South, Victoria|South Dandenong]] in December 2009, at which time it was expected that a year would pass before the wheel would reopen.<ref name=theage261209/>\n\n==2010==\nIn October it was reported that the viability of the wheel was in doubt after contractors stopped work because they had not been paid, although a spokeswoman for Southern Star Management Group denied this, stating that \"the construction process is extremely intricate and highly influenced by adverse weather conditions, including rain, wind, [and] hot and cold weather[.]\"<ref>[http://m.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/work-grinds-to-halt-on-southern-star-observation-wheel/story-e6frf7kx-1225934564252 Work grinds to halt on Southern Star Observation Wheel]</ref>\n\n==2011==\nIn January the first of the seven replacement spokes, manufactured by BMC in the [[Latrobe Valley]], was delivered to Docklands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad/observation-wheel-at-a-turning-point/story-fn6bfkm6-1225985227901|title=Observation wheel at a turning point|publisher=Herald Sun|date=11 January 2011}}</ref> In July the wheel was expected to be turning again by the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad/docklands-attraction-making-wheel-progress/story-fn6bfmgc-1226105063728|title=Docklands attraction making wheel progress|publisher=Herald Sun|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 November reconstruction work was in progress when the wheel broke free from its restraints and began turning in strong winds, resulting in minor injuries for one of the workers as they fled the site. The next day, Southern Star Management issued a statement saying that bracing used to erect the wheel had failed, and that no final completion date for the wheel had yet been confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/more-news/more-trouble-hits-southern-star-observation-wheel/story-fn7x8me2-1226208890059|title=Union blames Government for Southern Star Observation Wheel accident|publisher=Herald Sun|date=29 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-11-29/more-trouble-for-dockands-observation-wheel/3701980|title=More trouble for Docklands observation wheel|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> In December it was reported that the wheel was not expected to reopen before Easter 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/wheels-safety-in-doubt-union-20111204-1odk0.html|title=Wheel's safety in doubt: union|publisher=The Age|date=5 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==2012==\nIn January it was reported that an international team of experts including [[Arup Group Limited|Arup]] (who were involved in both the [[London Eye]] and the [[Singapore Flyer]] projects) and [[Hyder Consulting]] had been engaged in the redesign, and that reconstruction was now expected to be completed before the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smartplanet.com/blog/global-observer/melbournes-big-wheel-of-misfortune/3479|title=Melbourne's big wheel of misfortune|publisher=Smart Planet|date=28 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2012/01/melbournes-southern-star-wheel-to-get-\u2018world-first-led-lighting-system\u2019/|title=Melbourne's Southern Star Wheel To Get 'World First LED Lighting System'|publisher=Gizmodo|date=30 January 2012}}</ref> In June it was reported that the then owner ING Real Estate had repeatedly refused to announce an estimated completion date, but that an estimated date might be given at a briefing of state government officials planned for July.<ref name=heraldsun062012/>\n\nIn August it was reported that the wheel could reopen in January 2013, but only if there was \"no wind, no rain for the next four months\" - an unlikely scenario for Melbourne, \"a city renowned for extremely windy springs and rain that washes out the first cricket matches\". According to spokesman Ken Davis, 70 per cent of available construction time was being lost each week as cranes and lifts on the site could not operate in bad weather. He also stated that \"due to the complexity of the construction process, we are not in a position to make any announcements regarding a 2013 opening date\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/wheels-misfortune-continues-and-traders-are-not-happy-20121008-2784u.html|title=Wheel's misfortune continues, and traders are not happy|publisher=The Age|date=8 October 2012}}</ref> However, later that same month, after the final section of the rim was installed, he stated \"we're hoping it will be completed by the middle of next year\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/circle-complete-as-southern-star-reinvents-the-wheel-20121018-27t9p.html|title=Circle complete as Southern Star reinvents the wheel|publisher=The Age|date=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2013==\nIn January, ING Real Estate advised that the wheel would not reopen until the second half of the year,<ref name=\"Timing\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/wheels-reopening-at-least-six-months-away-20130122-2d4sg.html|title=Wheel's reopening at least six months away|publisher=The Age|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref> and on 27 April it was renamed as the Melbourne Star.<!--[[NOTE: Have dated the name change, 27 April 2013, based on an email from the PR firm for the wheel, who advised me that the name change took place on 27 April 2013. Not sure how to provide a reference for that as it is an email to me, not a public document. The PR person advised they did not issue a press release for the name change.]]--> On 25 August the opening was put back yet again, to March 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/docklands-traders-in-spin-over-1800-day-wait-for-melbourne-star-wheel-fix/story-fni0fit3-1226703753763|title=Docklands traders in spin over 1800-day wait for Melbourne Star wheel fix|publisher=Herald Sun 25 August 2013|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Three days later the first of the original cabins, which had been in storage since the original wheel was dismantled, was reinstalled. This took up to three-quarters of a day each, depending on weather conditions. The only substantial modification was an upgrade of their audio systems.<ref name=theage280813/>\n\n[[File:Melbourne Star August 2013 1.JPG|thumb|left|The first cars being reattached during the restoration in August 2013]]\nOn 11 October it was announced that Sanoyas had purchased the wheel from ING Real Estate for an undisclosed price, and that Melbourne Star Management Group would continue to manage it.<ref name=theage111013/><ref name=heraldsun111013>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/japanese-breathe-new-life-into-docklands-ferris-wheel-project/story-fni0fit3-1226738512996|title=Japanese breathe new life into Docklands ferris wheel project|publisher=Herald Sun|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> On 25 October, Sanoyas Holdings Corporation president Takashi Ueda announced that the company was aiming to reopen the attraction in ten weeks time. Advertisements for approximately 100 jobs began appearing on the Melbourne Star website and on the 'SEEK' recruiting website.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/docklands-troubleplagued-observation-wheel-set-to-open-in-ten-weeks/story-fni0fiyv-1226746281272|title=Docklands' trouble-plagued observation wheel set to open in ten weeks|publisher=Herald Sun|date=25 October 2013|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Reopening===\n[[File:Melbourne Star Observation Wheel 17th Dec 2013.jpg|thumb|Original passenger cabins fitted to the new wheel]]\nOn 6 December 2013 it was reported that construction work had been completed,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-06/southern-star-observation-wheel-set-to-reopen-soon/5139856|title=Melbourne Star observation wheel set to reopen soon, pending final tests|work=ABC News|date=6 December 2013}}</ref> and an announcement on the Star's website stated that the reopening would be in late December. Melbourne Star Management Group CEO Chris Kelly was quoted as saying \"We are working to the earliest possible opening date. We are now well into the commissioning process, which is the final stage before opening, but some activities do remain weather dependent.\"<ref name=melbournestar061213/>\n\nOn 15 December a promotional television advertising campaign commenced, and three days later it was announced that \"The Melbourne Star Observation Wheel will open for guests at 12 noon on Monday, December 23, 2013\"<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Melbourne Star advertisement |episodelink= |url=http://www.melbournestar.com/about-us/news.html |accessdate= |series= |serieslink= |first= |last= |network=Nine Network & Seven Network |station=Nine Melbourne and Seven Melbourne |location=Melbourne |date=15 December 2013 |began= |ended= |season= |seriesno= |number= |time=2pm & 9.11pm (0.5 minutes) |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> - almost five years after the original wheel was shut down in January 2009.<ref name=newscomau181213>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-reopens-after-five-years-in-time-for-christmas-holidays/story-fnii5sms-1226785614507|title=Melbourne's observation wheel opens next week|last1=Masanauskas|first1=John|date=18 December 2013|website=News|publisher=News Ltd|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 26 December, three days after the reopening, the wheel was stopped for several minutes while a cabin was inspected and taken out of service after passenger Marco Bresciani discovered a cracked window. CEO Chris Kelly described the damage as a \"very minor cosmetic issue\" caused by a bird strike. \"The glass has been inspected and our advice is that it is cosmetic and doesn't present any safety issues. It is in the process of being repaired.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/bird-strike-cause-of-crack-on-melbourne-star-observation-wheel-pod-window/story-fni0fit3-1226791565537 |title=Bird strike cause of crack on Melbourne Star Observation Wheel pod window  |last1=Mickelburough |first1=Peter |last2= |first2= |date=29 December 2013 |website=Herald Sun |publisher=News Ltd |accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the afternoon of 28 December the wheel was evacuated to allow a \"full inspection\" after the wheel unexpectedly stopped rotating. It was restarted 15 minutes later. Spokeswoman Sally Abbott said technicians had identified an \"isolated incident\" but refused to provide any details.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-spins-into-trouble-again/story-fni0fit3-1226791190469 Melbourne Star Observation Wheel spins into trouble again]</ref>\n\nThe [[Victorian Workcover Authority]] subsequently investigated safety complaints by several visitors.<ref name=heraldsu1226793373976>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/worksafe-to-probe-melbourne-star-observation-wheel/story-fni0fit3-1226793373976 WorkSafe to probe Melbourne Star Observation Wheel]</ref> Two families were reported to have been traumatised and left \"shaking and in tears\" after cabin eight became stuck and began tilting as the wheel turned. The operators confirmed that an alarm was triggered on both occasions but refused to say what triggered it, whether the two incidents were connected, if the same cabin was involved, if cabin eight remained in service, or whether it had been serviced between the two incidents. CEO Chris Kelly said the wheel remained open and safe for tourists even though one of the cabins had been taken out of service, and insisted that the cabin \"did not tilt or rock at any stage\". He refused to answer questions about the mechanics of the wheel or the cabins, or to confirm that the same cabin was involved in both incidents, saying: \"It is not our policy to comment on the specifics due to the highly complex engineering and electrical systems that operate the Star\" and \"It is not our policy to divulge this information as we don't want people to needlessly avoid specific cabins in the future.\"<ref name=heraldsu1226793373976/><ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-cabin-out-of-action-amid-worksafe-probe-20140102-306lj.html Melbourne Star Observation Wheel cabin out of action amid WorkSafe probe]</ref><ref>[http://heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-pod-fails-to-keep-level-says-family/story-fni0fit3-1226792674705 Melbourne Star Observation Wheel pod fails to keep level, says family]</ref>\n\n==2014==\n[[File:Aerial perspective of the Melbourne Star Observation Wheel.jpg|thumb|Melbourne Star, 2017]]\n\nOn 24 January the Star was again unexpectedly closed. Visitors arriving at the wheel were told the closure was due to \"windy conditions\", however a spokeswoman said \"operations have been temporarily suspended due to a software problem. Our technical services team are undertaking a comprehensive investigation to identify and correct the issue and we are expecting to resume operations later today.\"<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/travel/travel-incidents/melbourne-star-observation-wheel-halted-again-20140124-31dem.html Troubled wheel halted again]</ref> The wheel was closed from 11:00 until the following morning.<ref>[http://theaustralian.com.au/news/melbournes-docklands-observation-wheel-reopens-after-software-glitch/story-e6frg6n6-1226809701142 Melbourne's Docklands observation wheel reopens after software glitch]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Melbourne Star}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.melbournestar.com}}\n\n{{Ferris wheel}}\n{{Melbourne landmarks}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melbourne Star}}\n[[Category:Ferris wheels in Australia]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melbourne_Star"}
{"title_page": "Cho Yoon-je", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Cho Yoon-je\n|image = Cho Yoon-je.jpg\n|caption = Cho in 2018, visiting the U.S. Department of State\n|ambassador_from=South Korean\n|country= the United States\n|term_start = 30 August 2017\n|term_end = 25 October 2019\n|ambassador_from2=South Korean\n|country2=United Kingdom\n|term_start2=2005\n|term_end2=2008\n|president2=[[Roh Moo-hyun]]<br />[[Lee Myung-bak]]\n|president = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n|predecessor = [[Ahn Ho-young]]\n|successor   = [[Lee Soo-hyuck]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|02|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Busan|Pusan]], [[First Republic of Korea|South Korea]]\n|profession=Economist\n|alma_mater=[[Seoul National University]]<br />[[Stanford University]]\n}}\n\n{{Korean name|Cho}}'''Cho Yoon-je''' is a [[South Korea]]n diplomat who served as the South Korean ambassador to the [[United States]] between 2017-2019.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/attachments/summaries/KS-summary.pdf</ref> He was appointed as South Korea's ambassador to the U.S. in 2017 by South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2019/02/356_235646.html|title=Prof. Cho Yoon-je named S. Korean ambassador to US|date=2017-08-30|website=koreatimes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nCho is known for his deep and wide expertise on the global economy and finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171115000159|title=New Korean ambassador to US calls for strategic diplomacy|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2017-11-15|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Cho accumulated his experience in the economic and financial fields by working at such global organizations as the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and the International Monetary Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20170830005200315|title=(profile) S. Korea's next ambassador to U.S. known for economic expertise|date=August 30, 2017|website=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref> Cho served as Ambassador to the [[United Kingdom]] from 2005 to 2008 and as an economic adviser to former President [[Roh Moo-hyun]] from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/impact-player-cho-yoon-je|website=www.csis.org|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> He also headed [[Moon Jae-in]]'s policy think tank during the [[2017 South Korean presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3037772|title=Cho Yoon-je going to Washington, Victor Cha coming to Seoul|website=Korea JoongAng Daily|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> He is also an honorary professor of international studies at [[Sogang University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. Cho Yoon-je named S. Korean ambassador to US|url=http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/phone/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=235646|website=The Korea Times|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Myo-ja|first1=Ser|title=Cho Yoon-je going to Washington, Victor Cha coming to Seoul|url=http://mengnews.joins.com/view.aspx?aid=3037772|website=Korea Joongang Daily|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[South Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cho, Yoon-je}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of South Korea to the United States]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:South Korean economists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Cho Yoon-je\n|image = Cho Yoon-je.jpg\n|caption = Cho in 2018, visiting the U.S. Department of State\n|ambassador_from=South Korean\n|country= the United States\n|term_start = 30 August 2017\n|term_end = 25 October 2019\n|ambassador_from2=South Korean\n|country2=United Kingdom\n|term_start2=2005\n|term_end2=2008\n|president2=[[Roh Moo-hyun]]<br />[[Lee Myung-bak]]\n|president = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n|predecessor = [[Ahn Ho-young]]\n|successor   = [[Lee Soo-hyuck]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|02|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Busan|Pusan]], [[First Republic of Korea|South Korea]]\n|profession=Economist\n|alma_mater=[[Seoul National University]]<br />[[Stanford University]]\n}}\n\n{{Korean name|Cho}}'''Cho Yoon-je''' is a [[South Korea]]n diplomat who is served as the South Korean ambassador to the [[United States]] between 2017-2019.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/attachments/summaries/KS-summary.pdf</ref> He was appointed as South Korea's ambassador to the U.S. in 2017 by South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2019/02/356_235646.html|title=Prof. Cho Yoon-je named S. Korean ambassador to US|date=2017-08-30|website=koreatimes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nCho is known for his deep and wide expertise on the global economy and finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171115000159|title=New Korean ambassador to US calls for strategic diplomacy|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2017-11-15|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Cho accumulated his experience in the economic and financial fields by working at such global organizations as the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and the International Monetary Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20170830005200315|title=(profile) S. Korea's next ambassador to U.S. known for economic expertise|date=August 30, 2017|website=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref> Cho served as Ambassador to the [[United Kingdom]] from 2005 to 2008 and as an economic adviser to former President [[Roh Moo-hyun]] from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/impact-player-cho-yoon-je|website=www.csis.org|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> He also headed [[Moon Jae-in]]'s policy think tank during the [[2017 South Korean presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3037772|title=Cho Yoon-je going to Washington, Victor Cha coming to Seoul|website=Korea JoongAng Daily|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> He is also an honorary professor of international studies at [[Sogang University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. Cho Yoon-je named S. Korean ambassador to US|url=http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/phone/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=235646|website=The Korea Times|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Myo-ja|first1=Ser|title=Cho Yoon-je going to Washington, Victor Cha coming to Seoul|url=http://mengnews.joins.com/view.aspx?aid=3037772|website=Korea Joongang Daily|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[South Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cho, Yoon-je}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of South Korea to the United States]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:South Korean economists]]\n", "name_user": "NatGertler", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:who is served > who served", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cho_Yoon-je"}
{"title_page": "Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo\n| image                = \n| genre                = [[Animation]]\n| camera               = \n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| runtime              = 90 minutes\n| director             = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br>[[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]\n| producer             = Art Scott\n| executive_producer   = [[William Hanna]]<br>[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| starring             = \n| voices               = [[Henry Corden]]<br>[[Mel Blanc]]<br>[[Jean Vander Pyl]]<br>[[Gay Autterson]]<br>Joe Baker<br>Wayne Norton<br>[[Marilyn Schreffler]]<br>[[Frank Welker]]<br>Dolores Cantu-Primo\n| theme_music_composer = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| distributor          = [[Taft Broadcasting]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1979|12|08}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|1980|11|15}}\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 17 (59 segments)\n| list_episodes        = \n| preceded_by          = ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]''\n| related              = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''''' is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated]] package show and a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[The Flintstones]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera]] which aired on [[NBC]] from December 8, 1979 to November 15, 1980.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=210}}</ref> It contained the following three segments:\n\n*''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (a revival of ''The Flintstones'')\n*''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing|The Thing]]'' (based on the [[Marvel Comics]] superhero [[Thing (comics)|Thing]])\n*''[[The New Shmoo]]'' (based on the ''[[Li'l Abner]]'' comic strip character [[Shmoo]])\n\nThe show was a repackaging of episodes from ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'' combined with episodes of ''The New Shmoo''.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |page=108}}</ref>\n\nDespite the show's title, the segments remained separate and did not crossover with one another. The characters of [[Fred Flintstone]], [[Barney Rubble]], the [[Thing (comics)|Thing]] and [[Shmoo]] were only featured together in brief bumpers between segments, and the original half-hour episodes of ''The New Shmoo'' were now split into two-parters, allowing more mingling and mixing of the program's individual segments. In 1980, the Shmoo joined Fred and Barney as part-time police officers on the ''Bedrock Cops'' segment of ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]''.\n\nDespite having no narrative connection to the series, a television special called ''The Harlem Globetrotters Meet Snow White'' (also produced by Hanna-Barbera) originally aired in four segments as part of ''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo'' on September 27, October 4, 11 and 18, 1980.<ref>[https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/55852-Harlem-Globetrotters-Meet-Snow-White ''The Harlem Globetrotters Meet Snow White''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]], retrieved April 19, 2020.</ref>\n\nLike many animated series created by Hanna-Barbera in the 1970s, the show contained a [[Laugh track#Making their own|laugh track]], one of their last productions to do so.\n\n==Voice cast==\n\n===''The New Fred and Barney Show''===\n{{main article|The New Fred and Barney Show}}\n*[[Henry Corden]] as [[Fred Flintstone]]\n*[[Jean Vander Pyl]] as [[Wilma Flintstone]], [[Pebbles Flintstone]]\n*[[Mel Blanc]] as [[Barney Rubble]], [[Dino (The Flintstones)|Dino]]\n*[[Gay Autterson]] as [[Betty Rubble]]\n*[[Don Messick]] as [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble]]\n*[[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] as Mr. Slate\n\n===''The Thing''===\n{{main article|Fred and Barney Meet the Thing}}\n*Wayne Norton as Benjy Grimm\n*Joe Baker as [[Thing (comics)|The Thing]]\n*Noelle North as Kelly\n*[[Marilyn Schreffler]] as Betty, Miss Twilly\n*[[John Erwin]] as Ronald Radford\n*[[Art Metrano]] as Spike\n*Michael Sheehan as Turkey\n*[[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] as Dr. Harkness, Stretch\n\n===''The New Shmoo''===\n{{main article|The New Shmoo}}\n*[[Frank Welker]] as [[Shmoo]]\n*Dolores Cantu-Primo as Nita\n*[[Bill Idelson]] as Mickey\n*[[Chuck McCann]] as Billy Joe\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0298649|title=Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*{{tv.com show|fred-and-barney-meet-the-shmoo|Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*[http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/D-F/Fred_and_Barney_Meet_the_Shmoo/index.html ''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''] at the [[The Big Cartoon DataBase|Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Li'l Abner}}\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fred And Barney Meet The Shmoo}}\n[[Category:The Flintstones spin-offs]]\n[[Category:1979 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Li'l Abner]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Crossover animated television series]]\n[[Category:Television series set in prehistory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo\n| image                = \n| genre                = [[Animation]]\n| camera               = \n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| runtime              = 90 minutes\n| director             = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br>[[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]\n| producer             = Art Scott\n| executive_producer   = [[William Hanna]]<br>[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| starring             = \n| voices               = [[Henry Corden]]<br>[[Mel Blanc]]<br>[[Jean Vander Pyl]]<br>[[Gay Autterson]]<br>Joe Baker<br>Wayne Norton<br>[[Marilyn Schreffler]]<br>[[Frank Welker]]<br>Dolores Cantu-Primo\n| theme_music_composer = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| distributor          = [[Taft Broadcasting]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1979|12|08}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|1980|11|15}}\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 17 (59 segments)\n| list_episodes        = \n| preceded_by          = ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]''\n| related              = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''''' is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated]] package show and a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[The Flintstones]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera]] which aired on [[NBC]] from December 8, 1979 to November 15, 1980.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=210}}</ref> It contained the following three segments:\n\n*''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (a revival of ''The Flintstones'')\n*''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing|The Thing]]'' (based on the [[Marvel Comics]] superhero [[Thing (comics)|Thing]])\n*''[[The New Shmoo]]'' (based on the ''[[Li'l Abner]]'' comic strip character [[Shmoo]])\n\nThe show was a repackaging of old episodes of ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'') combined with episodes of ''The New Shmoo''.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |page=108}}</ref>\n\nDespite the show's title, the segments remained separate and did not crossover with one another. The characters of [[Fred Flintstone]], [[Barney Rubble]], the [[Thing (comics)|Thing]] and [[Shmoo]] were only featured together in brief bumpers between segments, and the original half-hour episodes of ''The New Shmoo'' were now split into two-parters, allowing more mingling and mixing of the program's individual segments. In 1980, the Shmoo joined Fred and Barney as part-time police officers on the ''Bedrock Cops'' segment of ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]''.\n\nDespite having no narrative connection to the series, a television special called ''The Harlem Globetrotters Meet Snow White'' (also produced by Hanna-Barbera) originally aired in four segments as part of ''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo'' on September 27, October 4, 11 and 18, 1980.<ref>[https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/55852-Harlem-Globetrotters-Meet-Snow-White ''The Harlem Globetrotters Meet Snow White''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]], retrieved April 19, 2020.</ref>\n\nLike many animated series created by Hanna-Barbera in the 1970s, the show contained a [[Laugh track#Making their own|laugh track]], one of their last productions to do so.\n\n==Voice cast==\n\n===''The New Fred and Barney Show''===\n{{main article|The New Fred and Barney Show}}\n*[[Henry Corden]] as [[Fred Flintstone]]\n*[[Jean Vander Pyl]] as [[Wilma Flintstone]], [[Pebbles Flintstone]]\n*[[Mel Blanc]] as [[Barney Rubble]], [[Dino (The Flintstones)|Dino]]\n*[[Gay Autterson]] as [[Betty Rubble]]\n*[[Don Messick]] as [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble]]\n*[[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] as Mr. Slate\n\n===''The Thing''===\n{{main article|Fred and Barney Meet the Thing}}\n*Wayne Norton as Benjy Grimm\n*Joe Baker as [[Thing (comics)|The Thing]]\n*Noelle North as Kelly\n*[[Marilyn Schreffler]] as Betty, Miss Twilly\n*[[John Erwin]] as Ronald Radford\n*[[Art Metrano]] as Spike\n*Michael Sheehan as Turkey\n*[[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] as Dr. Harkness, Stretch\n\n===''The New Shmoo''===\n{{main article|The New Shmoo}}\n*[[Frank Welker]] as [[Shmoo]]\n*Dolores Cantu-Primo as Nita\n*[[Bill Idelson]] as Mickey\n*[[Chuck McCann]] as Billy Joe\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0298649|title=Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*{{tv.com show|fred-and-barney-meet-the-shmoo|Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*[http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/D-F/Fred_and_Barney_Meet_the_Shmoo/index.html ''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''] at the [[The Big Cartoon DataBase|Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Li'l Abner}}\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fred And Barney Meet The Shmoo}}\n[[Category:The Flintstones spin-offs]]\n[[Category:1979 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Li'l Abner]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Crossover animated television series]]\n[[Category:Television series set in prehistory]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fred_and_Barney_Meet_the_Shmoo"}
{"title_page": "Venetian Lagoon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n<!-- *** Heading *** -->\n| name               = Venetian Lagoon\n<!-- *** Image *** -->\n| image              = Porto di Lido-San Nicol\u00f2.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption            = Aerial view of the Venetian Lagoon, showing many of the islands including Venice itself, center rear, with the bridge to the mainland\n| image_bathymetry   =\n| alt_bathymetry     =\n| caption_bathymetry =\n<!-- *** Country *** -->\n| basin_countries    = [[Italy]]\n| location           = [[Venice]], [[Veneto]], [[Italy]]\n| coords             = {{coord|45|24|47|N|12|17|50|E|region:IT_type:waterbody|display=title,inline}}\n| lake_type          = \n<!-- *** Family *** -->\n| inflow             = \n| outflow            = [[Adriatic Sea]]\n| date-built         = <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent lakes -->\n| date-flooded       = <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent lakes -->\n| agency             =\n| designation        =\n<!-- *** Dimensions *** -->\n| catchment          = \n| length             =\n| width              =\n| area               = {{convert|550|km2}}\n| depth              = {{convert|10.5|m}}\n| max-depth          = {{convert|21.5|m}}\n| volume             = \n| residence_time     =\n| shore              =\n| elevation          = {{convert|3|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| frozen             =\n| islands            =\n| cities             = [[Venice]], [[Campagna Lupia]], [[Cavallino-Treporti]], [[Chioggia]], [[Codevigo]], [[Jesolo]], [[Mira]], [[Musile di Piave]], [[Quarto d'Altino]], [[San Don\u00e0 di Piave]]\n<!-- *** Website *** -->\n| website            = \n| reference          = \n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_offname = Laguna di Venezia: Valle Averto\n| designation1_date = 11 April 1989\n| designation1_number = 423<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna di Venezia: Valle Averto|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/423|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Venetian Lagoon''' ({{lang-it|Laguna di Venezia}}; {{lang-vec|\u0141aguna de Venesia}}) is an enclosed bay of the [[Adriatic Sea]], in northern Italy, in which the city of [[Venice]] is situated. Its name in the [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[Venetian language|Venetian]] languages, ''{{lang|vec|Laguna Veneta}}''\u2014cognate of Latin ''{{lang|la|lacus}}'', \"lake\"\u2014has provided the English name for an enclosed, shallow [[embayment]] of salt water, a [[lagoon]].\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Venice Lagoon December 9 2001.jpg|thumb|left|The Venetian Lagoon]]\n[[File:TorcelloLagune.jpg|thumb|left|The island of [[Torcello]] seen from the Lagoon at low tide]]\nThe Venetian Lagoon stretches from the [[River Sile]] in the north to the [[Brenta (river)|Brenta]] in the south, with a surface area of around {{convert|550|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=off}}. It is around 8% land, including Venice itself and many smaller islands. About 11% is permanently covered by open water, or [[canal]], as the network of dredged channels are called, while around 80% consists of [[mud flat]]s, tidal shallows and [[salt marsh]]es. The lagoon is the largest [[wetland]] in the [[Mediterranean Basin]].<ref>{{cite news |author-link = Sylvia Poggioli |last = Poggioli |first = Sylvia |date = 7 January 2008 |url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17855145 |title = MOSE Project Aims to Part Venice Floods |work = Morning Edition |type = Radio program |publisher = [[NPR]] }}</ref>\n\nIt is connected to the [[Adriatic Sea]] by three [[inlet]]s: [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]], [[Malamocco]] and [[Chioggia]]. Sited at the end of a largely enclosed sea, the lagoon is subject to high variations in water level,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earth.esa.int/web/earth-watching/landsat-25-years/landsat-5-showcase/cities/-/article/venice-italy-1985-2003-|title=Venice, Italy (1985-2003) - 25 Years of Landsat 5 - Landsat 5 showcase - Earth Watching|website=earth.esa.int|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> the most extreme being the [[spring tide]]s known as the ''{{lang|it|[[Acqua Alta|acqua alta]]}}'' (Italian for \"high water\"), which regularly flood much of Venice.\n\nThe nearby [[Marano lagoon|Marano-Grado Lagoon]], with a surface area of around {{convert|160|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=off}}, is the northernmost lagoon in the Adriatic Sea and is called sometimes the \"twin sister of the Venice lagoon\".\n\n==Development==\nThe Lagoon of Venice is the most important survivor of a system of [[Estuary|estuarine]] lagoons that in Roman times extended from [[Ravenna]] north to [[Trieste]]. In the sixth century, the Lagoon gave security to Romanised people fleeing invaders (mostly the [[Huns]]). Later, it provided  naturally protected conditions for the growth of the [[Venetian Republic]] and its [[Thalassocracy|maritime empire]]. It still provides a base for a [[seaport]], the [[Venetian Arsenal]], and for [[fishing]], as well as a limited amount of [[hunting]] and the newer industry of [[fish farming]].\n\nThe Lagoon was formed about six to seven thousand years ago, when the marine transgression following the [[Ice Age]] flooded the upper Adriatic coastal plain.{{#tag:ref|This geological history follows {{harvp|Brambati|Carbognin|Quaia|Teatini|2003}}.<ref>{{cite journal |first1 = Antonio |last1 = Brambati |first2 = Laura |last2 = Carbognin |first3 = Tullio  |last3 = Quaia |first4 = Pietro |last4 = Teatini |first5 = Luigi |last5 = Tosi |last-author-amp = yes |year = 2003 |title = The Lagoon of Venice: Geological Setting, Evolution and Land Subsidence |journal = [[Episodes (journal)|Episodes]] |volume = 26 |issue = 3 |pages = 264\u2013268 |url = http://www.episodes.co.in/www/backissues/263/19Brambati.pdf |ref = harv }}</ref> |group=lower-alpha}} Deposition of river sediments compensated for the sinking coastal plain, and coastwise drift from the mouth of the [[Po River|Po]] tended to close tidal inlets with sand bars.\n[[File:2001-NASA-Satellitenaufnahme Venedig.jpg|thumb|Venetian lagoon from above]]{{clear}}The present aspect of the Lagoon is due to human intervention. In the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries, Venetian hydraulic projects to prevent the lagoon from turning into a marsh reversed the natural evolution of the Lagoon. Pumping of [[aquifer]]s since the nineteenth century has increased [[subsidence]].  Originally many of the Lagoon's islands were marshy, but a gradual programme of drainage rendered them habitable.  Many of the smaller islands are entirely artificial, while some areas around the seaport of the [[Mestre]] are also reclaimed islands.  The remaining islands are essentially [[dune]]s, including those of the coastal strip ([[Lido di Venezia|Lido]], [[Pellestrina]] and [[Treporti]]).\n\nVenice Lagoon was inhabited from the most ancient times, but it was only during and after the [[fall of the Western Roman Empire]]  that many people, coming from the [[Veneto|Venetian mainland]], settled in a number large enough to found the city of [[Venice]]. Today, the main cities inside the lagoon are Venice (at the centre of it) and [[Chioggia]] (at the southern inlet); [[Lido di Venezia]] and [[Pellestrina]] are inhabited as well, but they are part of Venice. However, the most part of the inhabitants of Venice, as well as its economic core, its airport and its harbor, stand on the western border of the lagoon, around the former towns of [[Mestre]] and [[Marghera]]. At the northern end of the lagoon, there is the town of [[Jesolo]], a famous sea resort; and the town of [[Cavallino-Treporti]].\n\n==Ecosystem==\n[[File:Food web of the Venice lagoon.png|thumb|upright=1| {{center|[[Food web]] diagram of the Venetian Lagoon <ref>Heymans, J.J., Coll, M., Libralato, S., Morissette, L. and Christensen, V. (2014). \"Global patterns in ecological indicators of marine food webs: a modelling approach\". ''PloS one'', '''9'''(4). doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0095845.</ref><ref>Pranovi, F., Libralato, S., Raicevich, S., Granzotto, A., Pastres, R. and Giovanardi, O. (2003). \"Mechanical clam dredging in Venice lagoon: ecosystem effects evaluated with a trophic mass-balance model\". ''Marine Biology'', '''143'''(2): 393\u2013403. doi:10.1007/s00227-003-1072-1.</ref>}}]]\n\nOccasionally, [[bottlenose dolphin]]s enter the lagoon, possibly for feeding.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Ferretti | first1 = Sabrina | last2 = Bearzi | first2 = Giovanni | title = Rare Report of a Bottlenose Dolphin Foraging in the Venice Lagoon, Italy | url = http://www.adriawatch.provincia.rimini.it/documenti/CETACEI/Ferretti_Bearzi.pdf | publisher = [[Tethys Research Institute]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402155709/http://www.adriawatch.provincia.rimini.it/documenti/CETACEI/Ferretti_Bearzi.pdf | archive-date = 2 April 2015 | url-status = dead | journal =  | access-date = 15 March 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe level of pollution in the lagoon has long been a concern<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Grancini | first1 = Gianfranco | last2 = Cescon | first2 = Bruno | last-author-amp = yes | year = 1971 | title = Observations of Dispersal Processes of Pollutants in Venice Lagoon and in the Po River Coastal Area | journal = Li\u00e8ge Colloquium on Ocean Hydrodynamics | volume = 2 | pages = 99\u2013110 | publisher = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Royale des Sciences de Li\u00e8ge }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | editor1-last = Lasserre | editor1-first = Pierre | editor2-last = Marzollo | editor2-first = Angelo | year = 2000 | title = The Venice Lagoon Ecosystem: Inputs and Interactions Between Land and Sea | series = Man and the Biosphere Series | volume = 25 | location = Paris | publisher = Parthenon | isbn = 978-92-3-103595-1 }}</ref>The large [[phytoplankton]] and [[macroalgae]] blooms of the late 1980s proved particularly devastating.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sfriso | first1 = A. | last2 = Pavoni | first2 = B. | last3 = Marcomini | first3 = A. | last4 = Orio | first4 = A. A. | last-author-amp = yes | year = 1992 | title = Macroalgae, Nutrient Cycles, and Pollutants in the Lagoon of Venice | journal = Estuaries | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 517\u2013528 | jstor = 1352394 | doi = 10.2307/1352394 }}</ref><ref name=\"Pranovi\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Pranovi | first = Fabio | last2 = Da Ponte | first2 = Filippo | last3 = Torricelli | first3 = Patrizia | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2007 | title = Application of Biotic Indices and Relationship with Structural and Functional Features of Macrobenthic Community in the Lagoon of Venice: An Example over a Long Time Series of Data | journal = Marine Pollution Bulletin | volume = 54 | issue = 10 | pages = 1607\u20131618 | doi = 10.1016/j.marpolbul.2007.06.010 | pmid = 17698152 | url = https://arca.unive.it/retrieve/handle/10278/3815/19079/Pranovi%20et%20al_07_MPB.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151225024059/https://arca.unive.it/retrieve/handle/10278/3815/19079/Pranovi%20et%20al_07_MPB.pdf | archive-date = 25 December 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref>  Researchers have identified the lagoon as one of the primary areas where non-indigenous species are introduced into the [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Occhipinti-Ambrogi | first1 = Anna | last2 = Savini | first2 = Dario | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2003 | title = Biological Invasions as a Component of Global Change in Stressed Marine Ecosystems | journal = Marine Pollution Bulletin | volume = 46 | issue = 5 | pages = 542\u2013551 | doi = 10.1016/S0025-326X(02)00363-6 | pmid = 12735951 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/10769699 }}\n</ref><ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Marchini | first1 = Agnese\n | last2 = Ferrario | first2 = Jasmine\n | last3 = Sfriso | first3 = Adriano\n | last4 = Occhipinti-Ambrogi | first4 = Anna\n | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2015\n | title = Current Status and Trends of Biological Invasions in the Lagoon of Venice, a Hotspot of Marine NIS Introductions in the Mediterranean Sea\n | journal = Biological Invasions\n | volume = 17 | issue = 10 | pages = 2943\u20132962\n | doi = 10.1007/s10530-015-0922-3\n| hdl = 10278/3661477\n | url = https://iris.unive.it/bitstream/10278/3661477/3/Biological%20Invasions.pdf\n }}\n</ref>\n\nNegative effects to the environment such as air pollution, loss of landscape, surface water pollution, erosion, and decreasing water quality have occurred due to the emission and impacts of cruise ships transiting into the Venetian Lagoon. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ejatlas.org/conflict/cruise-ships-in-venetian-lagoon|title=Cruise Ships impacting Venetian Lagoon, Italy {{!}} EJAtlas|last=EJOLT|website=Environmental Justice Atlas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Islands==\n[[File:Venedig-lagune.png|thumb|The Venetian Lagoon Islands]]\n[[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni, Venice aerial photo 2013.jpg|thumb|[[San Lazzaro degli Armeni]], has been an important center of Armenian culture for around 300 years.]]\n\nThe Venice Lagoon is mostly included in the [[Metropolitan City of Venice]], but the south-western area is part of the [[Province of Padua]].\n\nThe largest islands or archipelagos by area, excluding coastal reclaimed land and the coastal [[barrier beach]]es:\n*[[Venice]] 5.17&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sant'Erasmo]] 3.26&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Murano]] 1.17&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Chioggia]] 0.67&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Giudecca]] 0.59&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Mazzorbo]] 0.52&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Torcello]] 0.44&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sant'Elena]] 0.34&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[La Certosa]] 0.24&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Burano]] 0.21&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Tronchetto]] 0.18&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sacca Fisola]] 0.18&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Isola di San Michele|San Michele]] 0.16&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sacca Sessola]] 0.16&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Santa Cristina (island)|Santa Cristina]] 0.13&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n\nOther inhabited islands include:\n*[[Cavallino (Venice)|Cavallino]]\n*[[Lazzaretto Nuovo]]\n*[[Lazzaretto Vecchio]]\n*[[Lido di Venezia|Lido]]\n*[[Pellestrina]]\n*[[Poveglia]]\n*[[San Clemente (VN)|San Clemente]]\n*[[San Francesco del Deserto]]\n*[[San Giorgio in Alga]]\n*[[San Giorgio Maggiore]]\n*[[San Lazzaro degli Armeni]]\n*[[Santa Maria della Grazia]]\n*[[San Pietro di Castello (island)|San Pietro di Castello]]\n*[[San Servolo]]\n*[[Santo Spirito (Venetian Lagoon)|Santo Spirito]]\n*[[Sottomarina]]\n*[[Vignole]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of islands of Italy]]\n* [[Magistrato alle Acque]]\n* [[MOSE Project]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author-link = Horatio Brown |first = Horatio |last = Brown |title= Life on the Lagoons |year= 1884|title-link = Life on the Lagoons }} Additional editions printed in 1900, 1904, & 1909; paperback in 2008.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Laguna veneziana|Venetian Lagoon}}\n*[http://atlante.silvenezia.it/en/ Atlas of the Lagoon - 103 thematic maps and associated explanations grouped in five sections: Geosphere, Biosphere, Anthroposphere, Protected Environments and Integrated Analysis]\n*[http://www.silvenezia.it SIL \u2013 Sistema Informativo della Laguna di Venezia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040820232717/http://www.salve.it/uk/eco/destra/ecobase.htm Lagoon of Venice information]\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=venice,+italy&ll=45.367584,12.300568&spn=0.384961,1.315063&t=k&hl=en Satellite image from Google Maps]\n*[http://www.istitutoveneto.it/venezia/milva MILVa \u2013 Interactive Map of Venice Lagoon]\n*[http://www.comune.venezia.it/flex/cm/pages/ServeBLOB.php/L/IT/IDPagina/3836 Comune di Venezia, Servizio Mobilit\u00e0 Acquea, Thematic cartography of Venice Lagoon]\n*[http://www.photoshelter.com/c/enricomartino/gallery/Venices-lagoon-small-islands-5p-m-to-9-a-m/G0000bxVXDPTr.40/ Photo gallery] by [[Enrico Martino]] about Venice's lagoon small islands, night life\n\n{{Islands of Italy}}\n{{Islands of the Venetian Lagoon}}\n{{Portal bar|Geography|Islands|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:Venetian Lagoon| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of Venice]]\n[[Category:Chioggia]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bays of Italy]]\n[[Category:Bays of the Adriatic Sea]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in Italy]]\n[[Category:Lagoons of Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n<!-- *** Heading *** -->\n| name               = Venetian Lagoon\n<!-- *** Image *** -->\n| image              = Porto di Lido-San Nicol\u00f2.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption            = Aerial view of the Venetian Lagoon, showing many of the islands including Venice itself, center rear, with the bridge to the mainland\n| image_bathymetry   =\n| alt_bathymetry     =\n| caption_bathymetry =\n<!-- *** Country *** -->\n| basin_countries    = [[Italy]]\n| location           = [[Venice]], [[Veneto]], [[Italy]]\n| coords             = {{coord|45|24|47|N|12|17|50|E|region:IT_type:waterbody|display=title,inline}}\n| lake_type          = \n<!-- *** Family *** -->\n| inflow             = \n| outflow            = [[Adriatic Sea]]\n| date-built         = <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent lakes -->\n| date-flooded       = <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent lakes -->\n| agency             =\n| designation        =\n<!-- *** Dimensions *** -->\n| catchment          = \n| length             =\n| width              =\n| area               = {{convert|550|km2}}\n| depth              = {{convert|10.5|m}}\n| max-depth          = {{convert|21.5|m}}\n| volume             = \n| residence_time     =\n| shore              =\n| elevation          = {{convert|3|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| frozen             =\n| islands            =\n| cities             = [[Venice]], [[Campagna Lupia]], [[Cavallino-Treporti]], [[Chioggia]], [[Codevigo]], [[Jesolo]], [[Mira]], [[Musile di Piave]], [[Quarto d'Altino]], [[San Don\u00e0 di Piave]]\n<!-- *** Website *** -->\n| website            = \n| reference          = \n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_offname = Laguna di Venezia: Valle Averto\n| designation1_date = 11 April 1989\n| designation1_number = 423<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna di Venezia: Valle Averto|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/423|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Venetian Lagoon''' ({{lang-it|Laguna di Venezia}}; {{lang-vec|\u0141aguna de Venesia}}) is an enclosed bay of the [[Adriatic Sea]], in northern Italy, in which the city of [[Venice]] is situated. Its name in the [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[Venetian language|Venetian]] languages, ''{{lang|vec|Laguna Veneta}}''\u2014cognate of Latin ''{{lang|la|lacus}}'', \"lake\"\u2014has provided the English name for an enclosed, shallow [[embayment]] of salt water, a [[lagoon]].\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Venice Lagoon December 9 2001.jpg|thumb|left|The Venetian Lagoon]]\n[[File:TorcelloLagune.jpg|thumb|left|The island of [[Torcello]] seen from the Lagoon at low tide]]\nThe Venetian Lagoon stretches from the [[River Sile]] in the north to the [[Brenta (river)|Brenta]] in the south, with a surface area of around {{convert|550|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=off}}. It is around 8% land, including Venice itself and many smaller islands. About 11% is permanently covered by open water, or [[canal]], as the network of dredged channels are called, while around 80% consists of [[mud flat]]s, tidal shallows and [[salt marsh]]es. The lagoon is the largest [[wetland]] in the [[Mediterranean Basin]].<ref>{{cite news |author-link = Sylvia Poggioli |last = Poggioli |first = Sylvia |date = 7 January 2008 |url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17855145 |title = MOSE Project Aims to Part Venice Floods |work = Morning Edition |type = Radio program |publisher = [[NPR]] }}</ref>\n\nIt is connected to the [[Adriatic Sea]] by three [[inlet]]s: [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]], [[Malamocco]] and [[Chioggia]]. Sited at the end of a largely enclosed sea, the lagoon is subject to high variations in water level,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earth.esa.int/web/earth-watching/landsat-25-years/landsat-5-showcase/cities/-/article/venice-italy-1985-2003-|title=Venice, Italy (1985-2003) - 25 Years of Landsat 5 - Landsat 5 showcase - Earth Watching|website=earth.esa.int|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> the most extreme being the [[spring tide]]s known as the ''{{lang|it|[[Acqua Alta|acqua alta]]}}'' (Italian for \"high water\"), which regularly flood much of Venice.\n\nThe nearby [[Marano lagoon|Marano-Grado Lagoon]], with a surface area of around {{convert|160|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=off}}, is the northernmost lagoon in the Adriatic Sea and is called sometimes the \"twin sister of the Venice lagoon\".\n\n==Development==\nThe Lagoon of Venice is the most important survivor of a system of [[Estuary|estuarine]] lagoons that in Roman times extended from [[Ravenna]] north to [[Trieste]]. In the sixth century, the Lagoon gave security to Romanised people fleeing invaders (mostly the [[Huns]]). Later, it provided  naturally protected conditions for the growth of the [[Venetian Republic]] and its [[Thalassocracy|maritime empire]]. It still provides a base for a [[seaport]], the [[Venetian Arsenal]], and for [[fishing]], as well as a limited amount of [[hunting]] and the newer industry of [[fish farming]].\n\nThe Lagoon was formed about six to seven thousand years ago, when the marine transgression following the [[Ice Age]] flooded the upper Adriatic coastal plain.{{#tag:ref|This geological history follows {{harvp|Brambati|Carbognin|Quaia|Teatini|2003}}.<ref>{{cite journal |first1 = Antonio |last1 = Brambati |first2 = Laura |last2 = Carbognin |first3 = Tullio  |last3 = Quaia |first4 = Pietro |last4 = Teatini |first5 = Luigi |last5 = Tosi |last-author-amp = yes |year = 2003 |title = The Lagoon of Venice: Geological Setting, Evolution and Land Subsidence |journal = [[Episodes (journal)|Episodes]] |volume = 26 |issue = 3 |pages = 264\u2013268 |url = http://www.episodes.co.in/www/backissues/263/19Brambati.pdf |ref = harv }}</ref> |group=lower-alpha}} Deposition of river sediments compensated for the sinking coastal plain, and coastwise drift from the mouth of the [[Po River|Po]] tended to close tidal inlets with sand bars.\n[[File:2001-NASA-Satellitenaufnahme Venedig.jpg|thumb|Venetian lagoon from above]]\nThe present aspect of the Lagoon is due to human intervention. In the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries, Venetian hydraulic projects to prevent the lagoon from turning into a marsh reversed the natural evolution of the Lagoon. Pumping of [[aquifer]]s since the nineteenth century has increased [[subsidence]].  Originally many of the Lagoon's islands were marshy, but a gradual programme of drainage rendered them habitable.  Many of the smaller islands are entirely artificial, while some areas around the seaport of the [[Mestre]] are also reclaimed islands.  The remaining islands are essentially [[dune]]s, including those of the coastal strip ([[Lido di Venezia|Lido]], [[Pellestrina]] and [[Treporti]]).\n\nVenice Lagoon was inhabited from the most ancient times, but it was only during and after the [[fall of the Western Roman Empire]]  that many people, coming from the [[Veneto|Venetian mainland]], settled in a number large enough to found the city of [[Venice]]. Today, the main cities inside the lagoon are Venice (at the centre of it) and [[Chioggia]] (at the southern inlet); [[Lido di Venezia]] and [[Pellestrina]] are inhabited as well, but they are part of Venice. However, the most part of the inhabitants of Venice, as well as its economic core, its airport and its harbor, stand on the western border of the lagoon, around the former towns of [[Mestre]] and [[Marghera]]. At the northern end of the lagoon, there is the town of [[Jesolo]], a famous sea resort; and the town of [[Cavallino-Treporti]].\n\n==Ecosystem==\n[[File:Food web of the Venice lagoon.png|thumb|upright=1| {{center|[[Food web]] diagram of the Venetian Lagoon <ref>Heymans, J.J., Coll, M., Libralato, S., Morissette, L. and Christensen, V. (2014). \"Global patterns in ecological indicators of marine food webs: a modelling approach\". ''PloS one'', '''9'''(4). doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0095845.</ref><ref>Pranovi, F., Libralato, S., Raicevich, S., Granzotto, A., Pastres, R. and Giovanardi, O. (2003). \"Mechanical clam dredging in Venice lagoon: ecosystem effects evaluated with a trophic mass-balance model\". ''Marine Biology'', '''143'''(2): 393\u2013403. doi:10.1007/s00227-003-1072-1.</ref>}}]]\n\nOccasionally, [[bottlenose dolphin]]s enter the lagoon, possibly for feeding.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Ferretti | first1 = Sabrina | last2 = Bearzi | first2 = Giovanni | title = Rare Report of a Bottlenose Dolphin Foraging in the Venice Lagoon, Italy | url = http://www.adriawatch.provincia.rimini.it/documenti/CETACEI/Ferretti_Bearzi.pdf | publisher = [[Tethys Research Institute]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402155709/http://www.adriawatch.provincia.rimini.it/documenti/CETACEI/Ferretti_Bearzi.pdf | archive-date = 2 April 2015 | url-status = dead | journal =  | access-date = 15 March 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe level of pollution in the lagoon has long been a concern<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Grancini | first1 = Gianfranco | last2 = Cescon | first2 = Bruno | last-author-amp = yes | year = 1971 | title = Observations of Dispersal Processes of Pollutants in Venice Lagoon and in the Po River Coastal Area | journal = Li\u00e8ge Colloquium on Ocean Hydrodynamics | volume = 2 | pages = 99\u2013110 | publisher = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Royale des Sciences de Li\u00e8ge }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | editor1-last = Lasserre | editor1-first = Pierre | editor2-last = Marzollo | editor2-first = Angelo | year = 2000 | title = The Venice Lagoon Ecosystem: Inputs and Interactions Between Land and Sea | series = Man and the Biosphere Series | volume = 25 | location = Paris | publisher = Parthenon | isbn = 978-92-3-103595-1 }}</ref>The large [[phytoplankton]] and [[macroalgae]] blooms of the late 1980s proved particularly devastating.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sfriso | first1 = A. | last2 = Pavoni | first2 = B. | last3 = Marcomini | first3 = A. | last4 = Orio | first4 = A. A. | last-author-amp = yes | year = 1992 | title = Macroalgae, Nutrient Cycles, and Pollutants in the Lagoon of Venice | journal = Estuaries | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 517\u2013528 | jstor = 1352394 | doi = 10.2307/1352394 }}</ref><ref name=\"Pranovi\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Pranovi | first = Fabio | last2 = Da Ponte | first2 = Filippo | last3 = Torricelli | first3 = Patrizia | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2007 | title = Application of Biotic Indices and Relationship with Structural and Functional Features of Macrobenthic Community in the Lagoon of Venice: An Example over a Long Time Series of Data | journal = Marine Pollution Bulletin | volume = 54 | issue = 10 | pages = 1607\u20131618 | doi = 10.1016/j.marpolbul.2007.06.010 | pmid = 17698152 | url = https://arca.unive.it/retrieve/handle/10278/3815/19079/Pranovi%20et%20al_07_MPB.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151225024059/https://arca.unive.it/retrieve/handle/10278/3815/19079/Pranovi%20et%20al_07_MPB.pdf | archive-date = 25 December 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref>  Researchers have identified the lagoon as one of the primary areas where non-indigenous species are introduced into the [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Occhipinti-Ambrogi | first1 = Anna | last2 = Savini | first2 = Dario | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2003 | title = Biological Invasions as a Component of Global Change in Stressed Marine Ecosystems | journal = Marine Pollution Bulletin | volume = 46 | issue = 5 | pages = 542\u2013551 | doi = 10.1016/S0025-326X(02)00363-6 | pmid = 12735951 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/10769699 }}\n</ref><ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Marchini | first1 = Agnese\n | last2 = Ferrario | first2 = Jasmine\n | last3 = Sfriso | first3 = Adriano\n | last4 = Occhipinti-Ambrogi | first4 = Anna\n | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2015\n | title = Current Status and Trends of Biological Invasions in the Lagoon of Venice, a Hotspot of Marine NIS Introductions in the Mediterranean Sea\n | journal = Biological Invasions\n | volume = 17 | issue = 10 | pages = 2943\u20132962\n | doi = 10.1007/s10530-015-0922-3\n| hdl = 10278/3661477\n | url = https://iris.unive.it/bitstream/10278/3661477/3/Biological%20Invasions.pdf\n }}\n</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Islands==\n[[File:Venedig-lagune.png|thumb|The Venetian Lagoon Islands]]\n[[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni, Venice aerial photo 2013.jpg|thumb|[[San Lazzaro degli Armeni]], has been an important center of Armenian culture for around 300 years.]]\n\nThe Venice Lagoon is mostly included in the [[Metropolitan City of Venice]], but the south-western area is part of the [[Province of Padua]].\n\nThe largest islands or archipelagos by area, excluding coastal reclaimed land and the coastal [[barrier beach]]es:\n*[[Venice]] 5.17&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sant'Erasmo]] 3.26&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Murano]] 1.17&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Chioggia]] 0.67&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Giudecca]] 0.59&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Mazzorbo]] 0.52&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Torcello]] 0.44&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sant'Elena]] 0.34&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[La Certosa]] 0.24&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Burano]] 0.21&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Tronchetto]] 0.18&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sacca Fisola]] 0.18&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Isola di San Michele|San Michele]] 0.16&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Sacca Sessola]] 0.16&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n*[[Santa Cristina (island)|Santa Cristina]] 0.13&nbsp;km{{sup|2}}\n\nOther inhabited islands include:\n*[[Cavallino (Venice)|Cavallino]]\n*[[Lazzaretto Nuovo]]\n*[[Lazzaretto Vecchio]]\n*[[Lido di Venezia|Lido]]\n*[[Pellestrina]]\n*[[Poveglia]]\n*[[San Clemente (VN)|San Clemente]]\n*[[San Francesco del Deserto]]\n*[[San Giorgio in Alga]]\n*[[San Giorgio Maggiore]]\n*[[San Lazzaro degli Armeni]]\n*[[Santa Maria della Grazia]]\n*[[San Pietro di Castello (island)|San Pietro di Castello]]\n*[[San Servolo]]\n*[[Santo Spirito (Venetian Lagoon)|Santo Spirito]]\n*[[Sottomarina]]\n*[[Vignole]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of islands of Italy]]\n* [[Magistrato alle Acque]]\n* [[MOSE Project]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author-link = Horatio Brown |first = Horatio |last = Brown |title= Life on the Lagoons |year= 1884|title-link = Life on the Lagoons }} Additional editions printed in 1900, 1904, & 1909; paperback in 2008.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Laguna veneziana|Venetian Lagoon}}\n*[http://atlante.silvenezia.it/en/ Atlas of the Lagoon - 103 thematic maps and associated explanations grouped in five sections: Geosphere, Biosphere, Anthroposphere, Protected Environments and Integrated Analysis]\n*[http://www.silvenezia.it SIL \u2013 Sistema Informativo della Laguna di Venezia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040820232717/http://www.salve.it/uk/eco/destra/ecobase.htm Lagoon of Venice information]\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=venice,+italy&ll=45.367584,12.300568&spn=0.384961,1.315063&t=k&hl=en Satellite image from Google Maps]\n*[http://www.istitutoveneto.it/venezia/milva MILVa \u2013 Interactive Map of Venice Lagoon]\n*[http://www.comune.venezia.it/flex/cm/pages/ServeBLOB.php/L/IT/IDPagina/3836 Comune di Venezia, Servizio Mobilit\u00e0 Acquea, Thematic cartography of Venice Lagoon]\n*[http://www.photoshelter.com/c/enricomartino/gallery/Venices-lagoon-small-islands-5p-m-to-9-a-m/G0000bxVXDPTr.40/ Photo gallery] by [[Enrico Martino]] about Venice's lagoon small islands, night life\n\n{{Islands of Italy}}\n{{Islands of the Venetian Lagoon}}\n{{Portal bar|Geography|Islands|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:Venetian Lagoon| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of Venice]]\n[[Category:Chioggia]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bays of Italy]]\n[[Category:Bays of the Adriatic Sea]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in Italy]]\n[[Category:Lagoons of Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Bridgetkeenan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added negative effects to the ecosystem due to cruise ships.  Added citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venetian_Lagoon"}
{"title_page": "HWA Team", "text_new": "{{Motor racing team\n| name           = {{flagicon|GER}} HWA Team\n| logo           = Logo of HWA RaceLab.png\n| founded        = 1999\n| base           = [[Affalterbach]], [[Germany]]\n| founders       = [[Hans-Werner Aufrecht]]\n| current series = [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]] <br>  [[FIA Formula 3 Championship]]\n| former series  = [[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|DTM]] <br> [[Formula E]]\n| current drivers= '''Formula 2''' <br> 16. {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Artem Markelov]] <br> 17. {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Giuliano Alesi]] <br> '''Formula 3''' <br> 14. {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Jake Hughes]] <br> 15. {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Enzo Fittipaldi]] <br> 16. {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jack Doohan (racing driver)|Jack Doohan]]\n| website        = https://www.hwaag.com\n| driver titles  = '''[[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|DTM]]''':<br> [[2000 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2000]]: [[Bernd Schneider (racing driver)|Bernd Schneider]]<br> [[2001 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2001]]: [[Bernd Schneider (racing driver)|Bernd Schneider]]  <br> [[2003 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2003]]: [[Bernd Schneider (racing driver)|Bernd Schneider]] <br> [[2005 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2005]]: [[Gary Paffett]] <br> [[2006 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2006]]: [[Bernd Schneider (racing driver)|Bernd Schneider]] <br> [[2010 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2010]]: [[Paul di Resta]] <br> [[2015 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2015]]: [[Pascal Wehrlein]] <br> [[2018 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2018]]: [[Gary Paffett]]\n|team titles     = '''[[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|DTM]]''':<br> [[2000 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2000]]-[[2003 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2003]] [[2005 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2005]] [[2006 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2006]] <br> [[2008 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2008]]-[[2010 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2010]] [[2015 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2015]] [[2018 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2018]]\n}}\n'''HWA Team''', also known as '''HWA RACELAB,''' is the [[auto racing|motor racing]] team of '''HWA [[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]]''', a [[Germany|German]] company, based in [[Affalterbach]], that also develops and builds vehicles and components for [[Mercedes-AMG]].\n\nHWA was responsible for managing the AMG Mercedes team in the [[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]] (DTM). HWA AG was founded in 1999, and takes its name from [[Hans-Werner Aufrecht]], who established AMG in 1967. Towards the end of 1998 Aufrecht sold a majority interest in AMG to [[Daimler AG|DaimlerChrysler AG]]. As part of the process, the motor racing department and parts of the customised vehicles construction business were spun off and transferred to HWA AG.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hwaag.com/about-hwa.html |title=About HWA |access-date=2010-02-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502021647/http://www.hwaag.com/about-hwa.html |archive-date=2018-05-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHWA, currently managed by Thomaz Aufrecht, develops and builds the DTM racing cars and engines used by the HWA Team, and customer teams also competing in the DTM, such as [[Persson Motorsport]] and [[M\u00fccke Motorsport]]. They also develop and build engines for [[Formula Three]] racing cars, based on [[Mercedes-Benz]] production engines.\n\nIt was announced on 9 May 2018 that HWA will join [[Formula E]] for the [[2018\u201319 Formula E season|2018-19]] season.<ref>{{cite news |title=HWA AG join the Formula E grid for Season 5 \u2013 Formula E |url=http://www.fiaformulae.com/en/news/2018/may/hwa-ag-join-the-formula-e-grid-for-season-5/ |accessdate=23 October 2018 |work=www.fiaformulae.com |date=9 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Their drivers will be [[Gary Paffett]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kalinauckas |first1=Alex |title=HWA announces Paffett as first FE driver, reveals 2018/19 livery |url=https://www.autosport.com/fe/news/139254/hwa-reveals-paffett-as-first-fe-driver |accessdate=23 October 2018 |work=Autosport.com |date=8 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>, their reigning DTM champion<ref>{{cite news |title=Gary Paffett wins DTM title in spite of Ren\u00e9 Rast\u2019s six-pack |url=https://www.dtm.com/en/news/gary-paffett-wins-dtm-title-spite-ren-rast-s-six-pack-2018-10-14.html |accessdate=23 October 2018 |work=DTM.com |date=14 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> and former [[McLaren]] [[Formula One]] driver [[Stoffel Vandoorne]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edmondson |first1=Laurence |title=Vandoorne confirms Formula E move in 2019 |url=http://www.espn.com/f1/story/_/id/24987255/stoffel-vandoorne-confirms-formula-e-move-2019 |accessdate=23 October 2018 |work=ESPN.com |date=15 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>.\n\nIn October 2018, HWA was named as one of ten teams that would make up the grid for the [[2019 FIA Formula 3 Championship|inaugural]] season of the newly rebranded [[FIA Formula 3 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/f3/news/139333/mercedes-partner-hwa-for-new-fia-f3-series|title=FIA Formula 3 2019 team list revealed, including Mercedes ally HWA|last=Simmons|first=Marcus|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, the team entered into a partnership with [[Arden International]] for the [[2019 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arden-motorsport.com/press/arden-international-motorsport-and-hwa-racelab-to-initiate-formula-2-co-operation|title=Arden International Motorsport and HWA RACELAB to initiate Formula 2 co-operation|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref> On 16 October 2019 it was announced that HWA would take over Arden's entry completely for the [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2020 Season]] following their withdrawal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f2/news/931359/1/hwa-takes-over-arden-s-formula-2-entry-2020|title=Redirect Notice|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> The following month, the team named incumbent Arden driver [[Artem Markelov]] as their first driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2019/11_November/Markelov-signs-with-F2-newcomers-HWA-RACELAB/|title=MARKELOV SIGNS WITH F2 NEWCOMERS HWA RACELAB|date=November 22, 2019|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Racing results==\n===FIA Formula E Championship===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n! valign=\"middle\"| Year\n! valign=\"middle\"| Chassis\n! valign=\"middle\"| Powertrain\n! valign=\"middle\"| Tyres\n! valign=\"middle\"| No.\n! valign=\"middle\"| Drivers\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|1\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|2\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|3\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|4\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|5\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|6\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|7\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|8\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|9\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|10\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|11\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|12\n!style=\"width:26px;\"|13\n! valign=\"middle\"| Points\n! {{Tooltip|T.C.|Teams' Championship position}}\n|-\n! colspan=21 | HWA Racelab\n|-\n!rowspan=3| [[2018\u201319 Formula E season|2018\u201319]]\n|rowspan=3| [[Spark Racing Technology|Spark]] [[Spark SRT05e|SRT05e]]\n|rowspan=3| [[Venturi Automobiles|Venturi]] VFE05\n|rowspan=3| {{Michelin}}\n|\n|\n| [[2018 Ad Diriyah ePrix|ADR]]\n| [[2019 Marrakesh ePrix|MRK]]\n| [[2019 Santiago ePrix|SCL]]\n| [[2019 Mexico City ePrix|MEX]]\n| [[2019 Hong Kong ePrix|HKG]]\n| [[2019 Sanya ePrix|SYX]]\n| [[2019 Rome ePrix|RME]]\n| [[2019 Paris ePrix|PAR]]\n| [[2019 Monaco ePrix|MCO]]\n| [[2019 Berlin ePrix|BER]]\n| [[2019 Bern ePrix|BRN]]\n|colspan=2| [[2019 New York City ePrix|NYC]]\n!rowspan=3| 44\n!rowspan=3| 9th\n|-\n| 5\n| align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Stoffel Vandoorne]]\n| style=\"background:#CFCFFF;\"| 17\n| style=\"background:#EFCFFF;\"| Ret\n| style=\"background:#EFCFFF;\"| Ret\n| style=\"background:#CFCFFF;\"| 18\n| style=\"background:#EFCFFF;\"| '''Ret'''\n| 